This holiday season, I hope you‚Äôre doing a whole lot of this‚Äîenjoying the outdoors, spending time with friends, family or having quality time with yourself, drinking coffee, tea or something spiked, savouring the little moments and getting excited about the upcoming new yearüíô‚ú® Photo by the incredibly talented @kylekotajarvi

If you ask any of my friends, they‚Äôll tell you that my memory isn‚Äôt too good üôà That said, there are somethings that just stick for me. Like this morning on the lake. I can still remember it so clearly and it has almost been a year since. A couple of good friends, a campfire and a canoe... somethings are hard to forget I guess‚ò∫Ô∏èüí≠ Photo by @mikesugianto

A new decade and new year starts tomorrow! ü•≥üéä This year was a whirlwind for me. Focusing on the positives, here are a few stand out takeaways... It was the year that I quit my full-time job and threw myself into the freelance life. It was the year that I made the most incredible friendships. It was the year that my family grew stronger. It was the year that I went to a dozen new places that I‚Äôve never been before. It was the year I learnt the most about myself!
-
Some details about the photos in this post:
1. I was on a trip to the Dolomites with @mikesugianto and we ended up in Austria for less than 72 hours (we probably only slept like 10 hours total in 3 days).
2. I went to Patagonia for the first time. It was a trip with 7 pals‚Äîso hectic but so fun.
3. I explored Yosemite with @thismattexsits which kind of felt like a right of passage in some ways. So iconic.
4. I booked a last minute flight to the east coast of the US to chase fall colours with an epic squad of old and new friends. It was a fun-filled 5 days that‚Äôs for sure.
5. I went to Italy and fell in love with the country (like everyone does)
6. @mikesugianto and I also went to Iceland. It‚Äôs a country that is so diverse that 10 days wasn‚Äôt even a fraction of enough time to explore it.
7. I went to Hawaii with a great squad. It rained 90% of the time but we still walked away with great memories and a few good photos.
8. For the first trip of my new freelance career, I went to Idaho on a winter hot spring road trip. It was SO much fun and definietly recommend road trips like these. 
9. I explored Washington many, many, many times because I just can‚Äôt get enough of that state! So much hiking to do there.
10. Last but not least, I stayed home in beautiful British Columbia a lot because of this little thing called‚Ä¶ HOME LOVE!
-
I hope you have a wonderful and safe New Years Eve and have an even better 2020. Thank you for following along on my adventure. Without your support, I wouldn‚Äôt be here‚ù§Ô∏è‚ò∫Ô∏è
-
Photographers/pals/talented humans who helped me are tagged in the photos
I spent this day hiking, exploring and finding mountaintop caves in Sedona with one of my best pals, @juliiathompson... a pretty perfect day if you ask me!üß°üåµüåû

In the winter months, I tend to adventure further and I am able to stay outside longer when I have hot water to sip on‚Äîit really warms my body upüå®‚ùÑÔ∏è So, I‚Äôve been stoked to have my @avana bottle by my side this season so that my water remains hot even when I‚Äôm exploring in below freezing temperatures.
-
On my recent trip to Oregon, I filled up my @avana water bottle at the last gas station before driving to our sunrise spot‚Äîwhich was at least a few hours away. Once we got to the parking lot, we hiked, shot photos, hiked around a bit more, took in the views, hiked to the car, drove back a few hours and my water was s t i l l hot‚Ä¶ check out my story to be linked to their website. This is a purchase you won‚Äôt regret‚≠êÔ∏è #Avana¬†#DiscoveryAwaits¬†#MyAvanaBottle¬†#Beckridge¬†#ad

Photo one: me testing out the water. Photo two: me five minutes later‚ò∫Ô∏è
-
I still remember the moment when I was swimming in the lake. It wasn‚Äôt for a photo op, it was just me taking in the moment. The sun was setting, the water was a perfect temperature and felt really good on my sore muscles, the views were incredible and the mosquitos were finally at bay. I live for blissful moments like this‚ù§Ô∏è
-
Photos by @brendinkelly

perPostData.comment:
Yes. Yes. Yes. A million times yes. Cheers to forever @photograferg
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
photos by @_thebauers

29 on the 29th. Some might say that this is my golden birthday and when I look forward at the big things I have planned for this coming year I can help but think that‚Äôs true.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Looking back at this last year I feel an assortment of emotions. I am overwhelmed with gratitude for the amount of abundance I attracted into my life... I am overwhelmed with gratitude for the good friends that became best friends and all the new friends I‚Äôve met... Getting engaged to the man of my dreams.... Paying off all my debt... gratitude for all of you and your continued support.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
But I also look back and see the biggest internal struggles I‚Äôve faced yet... the heartbreak of my autoimmune diagnosis... the feelings of confusion... feeling lost in a life that‚Äôs quite different than I imagined and, a lot of the time, feeling at mercy to the numbers on a screen.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I‚Äôve heard it said by many from my older friends and mentors that your 20s are where you find yourself and your 30s are so amazing because you are so much more settled in who you are.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
As I look forward to this final year of my 20s I feel ready to make some much needed changes. I feel ready to step more fully into myself and trust that when I follow my heart my choices not only serve me, but also the greatest good of all. I‚Äôm ready to be the fullest version of myself even if it‚Äôs ‚Äútoo much‚Äù for some people out there. I‚Äôm ready to do the work that it takes so that next year, as I arrive to my next decade of life, I feel just a little more certain about what it means to be me.
Cruising into 2020 like...

I can‚Äôt get over how fun this weekend was! It‚Äôs funny because as someone who usually has so much to say in the captions I‚Äôm honestly feeling speechless. Thank you @greaterzionutah and @mountaingirls for such an incredible weekend. I can‚Äôt wait to plan my next trip back! And to my crew of adventure babes- miss you all already! #greaterzion #gzpartner2019
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
üì∏: @megkkee

If you‚Äôve been watching my stories than you know this weekend I‚Äôm hanging out in the @greaterzionutah area with @mountaingirls and a crew of 8 badass, beautiful women!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Yesterday we had the pleasure of going canyoneering into some super remote slot canyons with @paragonadventures . Canyoneering has been on my bucket list for such a long time now and it was just as fun as I imagined.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Utah is a super special place... I‚Äôm constantly blown away by how wild and unique the landscape is here. I love how every rock tells a story and that there‚Äôs a surprise around every corner...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

This may surprise you but it‚Äôs rare that I am naturally good at things when I get started. I feel like we live in such an instant gratification world sometimes that it‚Äôs easy to assume everyone who we know that‚Äôs good at something was simply ‚Äúa natural‚Äù.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Think about this: this is my 2,000th post here on Instagram... I have posted consistently here on this platform almost every day for the last 4.5 years now... there are sooo many people with a similar amount of followers as me who have posted wayyyyy less photos than I have. I was not an overnight success here on Instagram... but I continued to show up. Day after day. Month after month. Year after year. I stayed consistent.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I also didn‚Äôt start out very good at riding park on my snowboard.... or even being very good at snowboarding in general. My nickname in High School was ‚Äúwack style girl‚Äù because my riding style justified it... but I kept training... I kept trying... I kept falling... and now... after 18 years of snowboarding I feel pretty damn confident out there...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I could tell you a similar story for my yoga practice or teaching journey... my online health business... my photography and editing skills... I feel so grateful for levels of success I‚Äôve been able to reach in multiple aspects of my life but I know the truth... I get to celebrate because I didn‚Äôt give up when it got hard... or when I got bored... or when it seemed like I wasn‚Äôt ‚Äúgetting anywhere with it‚Äù. I just continued to show up.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Because of this instant gratification world we live in I think people overestimate what they might be capable of in the short run and if they don‚Äôt hit their goals so many people just give up... and move on to the next goal. But I also think that people seriously underestimate what‚Äôs possible over the long-run if they were to just stay consistent.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
So cheers to post number 2,000 and cheers to 2,000 more. Cheers to falling and failing and get back up again. Cheers to continuing to make steps when it feels hard or when everyone else doubts me. Cheers the magic that‚Äôs possible when you don‚Äôt give up.

What if I take my heart out of my chest and put it into this tiny little box... what if I show you my fullness, flaws and all? What if I take away the armour I wear in service of ‚Äúenoughness‚Äù? I sit and think.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I think I‚Äôm willing to risk it... To risk the heartache... to risk being misunderstood... because in the end I know that I‚Äôd rather be disliked for who I am than liked for who I‚Äôm not. I‚Äôd rather take a stand for the flaws and imperfections of the world... to love them. To love myself. Or at least try my best.

My teacher says, ‚Äúto the degree that we numb our pain we also numb our our happiness.‚Äù And so here I am... and here is my heart...

As I write this my pup, Tabor, is cuddled up next to me on the couch. It‚Äôs so wild to think that this dog who was scared of everything and everyone is now such a brave adventurer and excellent cuddle buddy‚Ä¶
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs been a little over a year now since we rescued her and even though we were told she was saved from a puppy mill we know relatively little about her background or the breeding practices of the place she was rescued from.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In Oct I partnered with @wisdompanel to celebrate Adopt a Shelter Dog month and as part of that partnership, we got to test out the #WisdomPanel 4.0 for ourselves and find out a bit more about Tabor‚Äôs genetic story.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
According to her results, she is 75% Mini American Shepherd (also known as mini Aussie) and 25% Australian Shepherd but the most impactful thing we learned was that she is positive for the MDR1 gene mutation! Dogs that have the MDR1 mutation may potentially have harmful reactions to commonly used medications, so informing Tabor‚Äôs veterinarian about this information is really important. They can identify appropriate medications to use that will not have these side effects so we‚Äôre able to keep Tabor safe and healthy.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Adopting from a shelter is INCREDIBLY rewarding but not knowing your dog‚Äôs history can feel a bit disempowering. Learning more about Tabor‚Äôs genetics has made me feel like I have more tools than ever to be the dog mama she deserves and I‚Äôm looking forward to as many years of adventures together as possible!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
If you are curious about learning more about your dog‚Äôs genetics check out @wisdompanel! For the holidays, use the code HOLIDAYS2019 for $20 off 4.0/Health products. And for those of you who have run your dog‚Äôs genetics before, what surprises did you have?? #WisdomPanelPartner #givethegiftofwisdom

I don‚Äôt think anyone I know would consider me a negative person... in fact, it‚Äôs probably quite the opposite. I find myself getting caught up on the things that didn‚Äôt go exactly as I had wanted them to and holding on to them... it‚Äôs really interesting actually. Now I‚Äôm not here to condone holding in negative emotions (I don‚Äôt think shoving things down ever served ANYONE in the long run) but I am personally trying to shift the focus...

I can‚Äôt change or control everything that happens to me but I do have control over how I react... and today? Today I‚Äôm choosing gratitude. Over. And over. And over again. Until gratitude is the habit and complaining is a distant memory. Who‚Äôs with me?

I‚Äôve heard it said before that those who find themselves living in the past often experience feelings of depression and those who live in the future are often overwhelmed with feelings of anxiety and that the path to freedom is learning to live in the present moment.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I don‚Äôt know about you but I find myself regularly caught up in the ‚Äúif, then‚Äù cycle. If I I achieve this goal, then I‚Äôll be happy... often leaving the joys of life as some distant future thing that I have to qualify for.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
For example, the pose in this picture... I used to dream of the day that my body could make this shape. I believed that by being able to do a pose like this I would  be considered a more credible teacher. So I worked and worked and when the day came that I actually was able to make this shape do you know where my mind immediately went? To the next goal. ‚ÄúWell this is nice and all but I‚Äôll REALLY be credible when I can get my top leg straight.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Because of my ‚Äúif, then‚Äù mentality I tend to hit a lot of my goals but often at the sake of the enjoyment of life. I get so caught up in what‚Äôs next that I often forget to feel the magic of the journey itself.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Here‚Äôs the thing, working on this pose actually did make me a better teacher... but it wasn‚Äôt the achieving of the pose that did. I spent hours on the mat in the process of learning this shape... because of that I gained incredible insights into the anatomy/biomechanics of the shoulders and the interplay of the hips, spine and lateral body. I also learned a lot about discomfort and what I‚Äôm capable of.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You‚Äôve heard me talk a lot lately about bringing more joy and lightheartedness into my life and the root of that for me is learning to be more in the present moment. Learning that even if I have goals for the future there‚Äôs no need to give up the joys along the way because in the end there will always be another pose to learn... another mountain to climb... another thing to cross of the list and, in the end, it‚Äôs journey there that matters most. It‚Äôs the ever unfolding present moments stacked on top of one another. It‚Äôs now. And now. And now. And NOW. (Photo by @alexisahrling)

When I was 17 years old I got my first tattoo. I gathered up enough strength to walk up to the tattoo place, hand the artist my ID clearly saying I wasn‚Äôt 18 yet and ask for a tattoo of the word ‚Äúfearless‚Äù on the inside of my middle finger. Truth be told I think I had so much conviction that the artist didn‚Äôt even question my age enough to look at the ID. He just made a photocopy and took me back to the chair.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I laugh a bit about this now because nearly 12 years later I know that the fearlessness I was searching for doesn‚Äôt actually exist. At the time I was searching for a reminder when I wanted to hit a big jump on my snowboard that I was going to be ok... that I ‚Äúhad it‚Äù... and being fearless seemed like the solution....
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve learned though, fear isn‚Äôt the problem and it isn‚Äôt going anywhere. While I‚Äôll likely never hit a big jump on my board ever again the fear comes up in other places... letting go of a ‚Äúsafe‚Äù career to follow my heart... public speaking... pouring my heart into words and putting it out there for the world to see and judge... making big scary steps towards goals with the total possibility of failing...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Sometimes our fears protect us... physiologically they‚Äôre designed to keep us alive. But more often than not these fears bubble up and we give them so much power that we stay small... and we play small with our lives...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I wish I could tell you that becoming fearless is the answer... I really do. But in reality I think what we are looking for when we seek to be fearless is actually strength... it‚Äôs courage. In a momentary boost of courage we can make a small decision that changes the whole trajectory of our lives... even if it‚Äôs just to prove to ourselves, for once, we are stronger then we think we are.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
So cheers to being brave. Cheers to looking at that ‚Äúthing‚Äù whatever it is and taking a big breath and saying, ‚ÄúI‚Äôve got this‚Äù. Cheers to fear... and cheers to courage.

Peace out 2019! I don‚Äôt know about all of you but this last year has been a rollercoaster. Some of my highest highs and lowest lows yet. Truth be told though... I‚Äôm grateful for all of it.

One of the biggest things I plan on shifting is learning to say no more. While I‚Äôve had some amazing opportunities come my way this year I‚Äôve found my voice lost in a sea of other people‚Äôs opinions of what I ‚Äúshould‚Äù be doing.

This may surprise you but it‚Äôs rare that I am naturally good at things when I get started. I feel like we live in such an instant gratification world sometimes that it‚Äôs easy to assume everyone who we know that‚Äôs good at something was simply ‚Äúa natural‚Äù.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Think about this: this is my 2,000th post here on Instagram... I have posted consistently here on this platform almost every day for the last 4.5 years now... there are sooo many people with a similar amount of followers as me who have posted wayyyyy less photos than I have. I was not an overnight success here on Instagram... but I continued to show up. Day after day. Month after month. Year after year. I stayed consistent.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I also didn‚Äôt start out very good at riding park on my snowboard.... or even being very good at snowboarding in general. My nickname in High School was ‚Äúwack style girl‚Äù because my riding style justified it... but I kept training... I kept trying... I kept falling... and now... after 18 years of snowboarding I feel pretty damn confident out there...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I could tell you a similar story for my yoga practice or teaching journey... my online health business... my photography and editing skills... I feel so grateful for levels of success I‚Äôve been able to reach in multiple aspects of my life but I know the truth... I get to celebrate because I didn‚Äôt give up when it got hard... or when I got bored... or when it seemed like I wasn‚Äôt ‚Äúgetting anywhere with it‚Äù. I just continued to show up.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Because of this instant gratification world we live in I think people overestimate what they might be capable of in the short run and if they don‚Äôt hit their goals so many people just give up... and move on to the next goal. But I also think that people seriously underestimate what‚Äôs possible over the long-run if they were to just stay consistent.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
So cheers to post number 2,000 and cheers to 2,000 more. Cheers to falling and failing and get back up again. Cheers to continuing to make steps when it feels hard or when everyone else doubts me. Cheers the magic that‚Äôs possible when you don‚Äôt give up.

As I write this my pup, Tabor, is cuddled up next to me on the couch. It‚Äôs so wild to think that this dog who was scared of everything and everyone is now such a brave adventurer and excellent cuddle buddy‚Ä¶
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
It‚Äôs been a little over a year now since we rescued her and even though we were told she was saved from a puppy mill we know relatively little about her background or the breeding practices of the place she was rescued from.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In Oct I partnered with @wisdompanel to celebrate Adopt a Shelter Dog month and as part of that partnership, we got to test out the #WisdomPanel 4.0 for ourselves and find out a bit more about Tabor‚Äôs genetic story.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
According to her results, she is 75% Mini American Shepherd (also known as mini Aussie) and 25% Australian Shepherd but the most impactful thing we learned was that she is positive for the MDR1 gene mutation! Dogs that have the MDR1 mutation may potentially have harmful reactions to commonly used medications, so informing Tabor‚Äôs veterinarian about this information is really important. They can identify appropriate medications to use that will not have these side effects so we‚Äôre able to keep Tabor safe and healthy.

When I was 17 years old I got my first tattoo. I gathered up enough strength to walk up to the tattoo place, hand the artist my ID clearly saying I wasn‚Äôt 18 yet and ask for a tattoo of the word ‚Äúfearless‚Äù on the inside of my middle finger. Truth be told I think I had so much conviction that the artist didn‚Äôt even question my age enough to look at the ID. He just made a photocopy and took me back to the chair.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I laugh a bit about this now because nearly 12 years later I know that the fearlessness I was searching for doesn‚Äôt actually exist. At the time I was searching for a reminder when I wanted to hit a big jump on my snowboard that I was going to be ok... that I ‚Äúhad it‚Äù... and being fearless seemed like the solution....
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve learned though, fear isn‚Äôt the problem and it isn‚Äôt going anywhere. While I‚Äôll likely never hit a big jump on my board ever again the fear comes up in other places... letting go of a ‚Äúsafe‚Äù career to follow my heart... public speaking... pouring my heart into words and putting it out there for the world to see and judge... making big scary steps towards goals with the total possibility of failing...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Sometimes our fears protect us... physiologically they‚Äôre designed to keep us alive. But more often than not these fears bubble up and we give them so much power that we stay small... and we play small with our lives...
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I wish I could tell you that becoming fearless is the answer... I really do. But in reality I think what we are looking for when we seek to be fearless is actually strength... it‚Äôs courage. In a momentary boost of courage we can make a small decision that changes the whole trajectory of our lives... even if it‚Äôs just to prove to ourselves, for once, we are stronger then we think we are.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
So cheers to being brave. Cheers to looking at that ‚Äúthing‚Äù whatever it is and taking a big breath and saying, ‚ÄúI‚Äôve got this‚Äù. Cheers to fear... and cheers to courage.

I think sometimes we over glorify big trips where we have to fly far away and forget that hopping in the car for a short adventure can be just as magical and exciting. If you need to re-up on any of your travel gear feel free to use the code ‚ÄúARIELLE15‚Äù for 15% off *some exclusions apply*
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
p.s. since I know you are going to ask, the fleece I‚Äôm wearing is called the @backcountry Sherpa Fleece Jacket and I‚Äôm totally obsessed. #findyourbackcountry #backcountrypartner

I‚Äôve heard it said before that those who find themselves living in the past often experience feelings of depression and those who live in the future are often overwhelmed with feelings of anxiety and that the path to freedom is learning to live in the present moment.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I don‚Äôt know about you but I find myself regularly caught up in the ‚Äúif, then‚Äù cycle. If I I achieve this goal, then I‚Äôll be happy... often leaving the joys of life as some distant future thing that I have to qualify for.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
For example, the pose in this picture... I used to dream of the day that my body could make this shape. I believed that by being able to do a pose like this I would  be considered a more credible teacher. So I worked and worked and when the day came that I actually was able to make this shape do you know where my mind immediately went? To the next goal. ‚ÄúWell this is nice and all but I‚Äôll REALLY be credible when I can get my top leg straight.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Because of my ‚Äúif, then‚Äù mentality I tend to hit a lot of my goals but often at the sake of the enjoyment of life. I get so caught up in what‚Äôs next that I often forget to feel the magic of the journey itself.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Here‚Äôs the thing, working on this pose actually did make me a better teacher... but it wasn‚Äôt the achieving of the pose that did. I spent hours on the mat in the process of learning this shape... because of that I gained incredible insights into the anatomy/biomechanics of the shoulders and the interplay of the hips, spine and lateral body. I also learned a lot about discomfort and what I‚Äôm capable of.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You‚Äôve heard me talk a lot lately about bringing more joy and lightheartedness into my life and the root of that for me is learning to be more in the present moment. Learning that even if I have goals for the future there‚Äôs no need to give up the joys along the way because in the end there will always be another pose to learn... another mountain to climb... another thing to cross of the list and, in the end, it‚Äôs journey there that matters most. It‚Äôs the ever unfolding present moments stacked on top of one another. It‚Äôs now. And now. And now. And NOW. (Photo by @alexisahrling)

#ad It‚Äôs crazy to think that New Year‚Äôs Day is less than one week away! Last week I shared that my main wellness New Year‚Äôs resolution is to have as much fun as possible and stop taking life so seriously. Part of achieving that goal will be through booking a few trips on @bookingcom that are truly just for fun‚Ä¶ It‚Äôs been awhile since I didn‚Äôt let work creep in!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Do you want a chance to win $2,020 so you can #BookYourResolution? @bookingcom is hosting a contest and all you have to do is post your most inspiring and creative New Year‚Äôs resolutions on IG or TW and use the tag #BookMyResolution and #contest. Pop over to my stories to learn more about the contest! Cheers to the most fun new year yet! US residents only. Visit @bookingcom link in bio for T&C‚Äôs.

29 on the 29th. Some might say that this is my golden birthday and when I look forward at the big things I have planned for this coming year I can help but think that‚Äôs true.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Looking back at this last year I feel an assortment of emotions. I am overwhelmed with gratitude for the amount of abundance I attracted into my life... I am overwhelmed with gratitude for the good friends that became best friends and all the new friends I‚Äôve met... Getting engaged to the man of my dreams.... Paying off all my debt... gratitude for all of you and your continued support.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
But I also look back and see the biggest internal struggles I‚Äôve faced yet... the heartbreak of my autoimmune diagnosis... the feelings of confusion... feeling lost in a life that‚Äôs quite different than I imagined and, a lot of the time, feeling at mercy to the numbers on a screen.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I‚Äôve heard it said by many from my older friends and mentors that your 20s are where you find yourself and your 30s are so amazing because you are so much more settled in who you are.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
As I look forward to this final year of my 20s I feel ready to make some much needed changes. I feel ready to step more fully into myself and trust that when I follow my heart my choices not only serve me, but also the greatest good of all. I‚Äôm ready to be the fullest version of myself even if it‚Äôs ‚Äútoo much‚Äù for some people out there. I‚Äôm ready to do the work that it takes so that next year, as I arrive to my next decade of life, I feel just a little more certain about what it means to be me.

First of all, I just want to say thank you so much for all the birthday wishes yesterday! Between Christmas and my birthday and all the activities that go along with them, this always ends up being one of my favorite weeks of the year!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
CONTEST CLOSED. Winner is @heythererae The holidays themselves may be over but I am super excited to partner with @eddiebauer to give a little New Year‚Äôs present to one of you! Want a chance to win a $200 @eddiebauer gift card? Entering is super easy! All you need to do is follow me and @eddiebauer, like this photo, and tag a friend in the comments below. You have until midnight on New Year‚Äôs Eve to enter! For all the rules and regulations visit http://bit.ly/2rIvFxT. As I say with any giveaway, may the odds be ever in your favor!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
P.s. in this photo I‚Äôm wearing some of my favorite @eddiebauer winter pieces. For more details on what I‚Äôm wearing pop over to my stories! #EBcontributer #liveyouradventure

Peace out 2019! I don‚Äôt know about all of you but this last year has been a rollercoaster. Some of my highest highs and lowest lows yet. Truth be told though... I‚Äôm grateful for all of it.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I learned A LOT about what I don‚Äôt want for my life and I see this New Years as an opportunity to be more intentional with taking my life the direction I want to take it.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
One of the biggest things I plan on shifting is learning to say no more. While I‚Äôve had some amazing opportunities come my way this year I‚Äôve found my voice lost in a sea of other people‚Äôs opinions of what I ‚Äúshould‚Äù be doing.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
My teacher always says, ‚Äúif you don‚Äôt consciously choose your future you past will choose it for you‚Äù so I plan on taking some time today to get clear on my vision for 2020 (pun intended üòú).
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Something else I learned a few years ago was that you have to be willing to let go of who you are... or even who you could be... to become who you are meant to be so I‚Äôm ready to say goodbye to who I‚Äôd be if I followed all the shoulds... or if I kept doing exactly what I‚Äôve always done... so that I can be there person my heart is calling me to be.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
So peace out 2019... Thank you for everything you taught me. 2020- let‚Äôs fucking do this üôåüèª
Cruising into 2020 like...

#ad Did you know that most New Year‚Äôs resolutions are forgotten or given up on within the first few weeks of January? I have definitely had many New Year‚Äôs resolutions fall to the wayside over the years but if I look back to the one‚Äôs that didn‚Äôt‚Ä¶ those things that started as resolutions and eventually became a new habits/lifestyle‚Ä¶ they were on my calendar!
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You all know one of my resolutions this year was to plan some trips that are just for fun with no work allowed. Thanks to @bookingcom, I already have a few on my calendar. Even if you‚Äôve already started to slide on your resolutions it‚Äôs not too late to reset yourself and #BookYourResolution!! Where are your New Year‚Äôs resolutions taking you this year?

Today I was up way before the sun. I‚Äôm going on my first hut trip today and I think excitement has gotten the best of me. Even though I grew up here in Colorado, my focus was on riding park so the whole idea of adventure skiing/snowboarding is new to me.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
This will be my split board‚Äôs first adventure off the resort and my first time skinning up something that wasn‚Äôt recently groomed... I don‚Äôt know if any of you can relate but I‚Äôve wanted to get into the backcountry for awhile now but I just didn‚Äôt know where to start.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Finally, this year I just pulled the trigger... I stopped waiting for something to happen and made it happen! This hut trip is guided and also an avalanche course so I can get some real hands on experience with some people who REALLY know their stuff.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
One of the biggest things I‚Äôve learned over the last few years is in order to achieve my goals I have to be comfortable being uncomfortable... I have to be ok with not having it all figured out and starting anyways. I have to ask the right questions... seek out the right people... and be willing to invest in myself and my future.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
So maybe this is just a 3-day hut trip... or maybe this is the gateway into the next chapter of my life. Either way, I‚Äôm excited for the adventure.

When your seasonal depression is in full swing but you‚Äôre also slightly in the holiday spirit üòëüíÅ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
üì∑: @abbihearne

I am the child of an extremely difficult divorce.
A divorce that shaped my teenage years and fostered a grudge that I held on to clear into my mid-twenties.
And so, for those of us who‚Äôs families don‚Äôt look like something out of a Hallmark card, Christmas can be especially brutal.
My mom and I spent a lot of our holidays off on odd excursions together. Whether it was to foster her sense of adventure in me or to distract from the fact that we were sort of on our own...I can‚Äôt be certain. But it worked.
We‚Äôd go off and stay in random hotels in the city or spend hours driving through the dark corners of Vermont looking for tiny Bed & Breakfasts.
Christmas has been different every single year since I was 15. And so, that lack of tradition has become tradition in and of itself.
Keith and the dogs and I have spent Christmas Eve asleep in the back of his pickup truck in the dirt parking lot of Horseshoe Bend. We‚Äôve eaten pancakes around a campfire in the middle of the desert and been trapped in a whiteout snowstorm on the side of the road and shared the first moments of Christmas on a crowded red eye flight full of strangers.
This year is different yet again, as Keith and I will spend tomorrow in the hospital getting some tests done. Some Christmas Eve huh?! (More on that later though.)
The simple fact is, we don‚Äôt get to choose a lot of what happens to us in this life. We are products of circumstance and luck and timing.
What we do get to choose is what we do with all of that. Perspective is always a choice.
And so, this holiday season, whether you‚Äôre out in the wild or alone in an apartment or surrounded by family or stuck somewhere less than ideal...I hope you find your joy.
That‚Äôs the only thing this was all supposed to be about anyway, right?
Wishing you all a very happy Christmas üß°
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
üì∑: my pal @abbihearne

At least once a week I burst out laughing over the fact that people used to see photos of Dagwood‚Äôs butthole and ask if it was his ‚Äútail hole‚Äù as if he was some sort of Mr Potato Head figurine whose various limbs just popped in and out. üò≠üòÇ (Also, if you were one of those people, please don‚Äôt be offended. You brought me laughter in a dark, dark time and to be fair, Dagwood‚Äôs hind-end looked absolutely bizarre for a really long time til his hair started coming back.)

We tend to live in a society that glamorizes the whole ‚ÄòEat Pray Love‚Äô type thing...
If you‚Äôre struggling, run away as far as you can to discover who you are. That‚Äôs all fine and well and I‚Äôve got nothing against it. Hell, I‚Äôve basically made a whole life out of running away. But I‚Äôd like to lend a moment in the spotlight to the things many of us are lucky enough to have right within reach.
Old friends and old photo albums and all the music we used to dance to when we were kids. Stories told by our parents and their parents. Memories of times we loved and times we didn‚Äôt love so much, but survived nonetheless.
I‚Äôve spent the past few months looking back instead of ahead, and I‚Äôm sure that sounds like a bad thing at first glance, but it‚Äôs been wonderful. I‚Äôve visited childhood friends and surprised my grandmother back East. I‚Äôve snuggled my nephew and played board games with my brother and dug through old photos of my beloved childhood home that used to be too painful to look at.
And I suppose what I‚Äôve come to find in all of this is a much needed sense of perspective in this busy round-and-round life of mine...
Sometimes remembering who we were is just as important as discovering who we are.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
First photo: @abbihearne
Second photo: My mom üòâ
If I was a better photographer, I‚Äôd probably have known how to get rid of all that sun flare, but somehow it seemed more fitting exactly how it was... üïä

A week after Keith and I started dating, we walked down to a boardwalk overlooking the Long Island Sound.
We sat under a blue moon and talked about all the things you talk about when you're pretty certain you're in love.
Suddenly, out over the water, a horizontal bolt of lightning split the purple night sky.
For the next 15 minutes, bolt after bolt after bolt ripped the clouds apart, parallel to the horizon, as though the world had been spun on its side.
There wasn't a breeze...a drop of rain...a hint of thunder...
It was as though someone had snuck behind the clouds and was flicking switches and pulling wires.
I'd never seen lightning like that in my life, and I've never seen lightning like that since.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
üì∑: @abbihearne

While Dagwood may not exactly ‚Äúappreciate‚Äù the finer things in life üòÇ, Bucket spent the past 48 hours living the life she believes she deserves üôèüèªüëë. Thanks for having us, @waldorfparkcity! Now, back to the dirt üåµ #WaldorfParkCity

Dashing through the no üòë

The first time I stepped into this canyon was Valentine‚Äôs Day of 2015. I found a small patch of sunlight on the south-facing wall and pressed myself up against the sandstone. I opened my eyes maybe 20 minutes later and found a set of vibrant yellow ones staring back at me. Directly across, in a large inlet among the wacos, two owls watched me inquisitively.
Slowly, I reached for my camera and managed to capture this photograph you see here.
I sat in that canyon with the dogs running around careless for almost 3 hours until my sunlight was gone, and those owls sat there too.
Every single winter, I‚Äôve gone back into this canyon and every single winter, one or more owls have been in this very nest.
So I go each year and I talk to them.
The dogs can‚Äôt see them. They must think I‚Äôve gone mad sitting there talking up into the sky, so they tear off around the corner, uninterested, and it‚Äôs just me and the owls.
It‚Äôs hard these days to come upon things that haven‚Äôt changed in 5 years. The world is so rapidly growing and changing and expanding and imploding.
Every year, I hold my breath rounding the corner to where I hope our eyes will meet. And every year, I‚Äôve cried seeing those sunflower eyes exactly where they should be.
It‚Äôs a gift to slip through these cracks in the earth out here and know that at least, for now, those that call them home have their shelter. I was so happy to see them again today.
So...if at any point in the last few years you‚Äôve asked where I am, perhaps you‚Äôll understand why I don‚Äôt answer.
Did you poop in this house??

One of the most important things I‚Äôve done for myself in the last year or so is to stop trying to be good at everything and just focus on being great at one thing.
I‚Äôm a great writer. But I‚Äôm just an okay environmentalist...just a decent advocate...just a relatively passable photographer...just a mildly politically aware citizen. I try my best, but I can‚Äôt be great at it all.
And yet sometimes I feel guilty for not being vocal enough about every single issue of our time, as though my somewhat public presence warrants me to be an expert at everything. I suppose I could pretend to be...
I could post links to websites I didn‚Äôt read, chime in on arguments I don‚Äôt know enough about, pretend to speak on experiences I‚Äôve never actually lived. I certainly see enough people doing that anyway...
But few things seem more disingenuous.
And I‚Äôm not here to be disingenuous.
What I‚Äôve tried to be better at, instead, is listening. Listening to people who ARE the experts in these areas, the people who HAVE lived these experiences.
It‚Äôs one thing to use your voice, but it‚Äôs a whole other thing to speak over other more knowledgeable voices for the sake of your own appearance.
And so I thought perhaps this post could serve as a community bulletin board. Are there accounts you like that discuss certain topics, certain demographics, certain issues that you want people to know about? I‚Äôd love if you‚Äôd post them here.
Here‚Äôs a few of mine: @hownottotravellikeabasicbitch @outdooradvocacy @pattiegonia @unlikelyhikers @browngirlsclimb @accessfund @nativesoutdoors @sheliftgrams

I've taken an odd sense of comfort in watching how my life has begun to wear itself on my face.
The slowly spreading lines at the corner of each eye...the subtle softening of the skin on my chest...the roadmap of wrinkles stretching out across my forehead...the mural of scars dotting my knees and elbows...the hands that are starting to look just like my mama's...
Make no mistake, time comes for all of us.
It takes the color from our hair and the strength from our skin and the resilience from our bones.
In the end, we're not much more than the stories we can tell.
I intend to make them good ones.

Bucket catching a ride with her Uncle Mark through a slot canyon like the true queen that she is. We decided recently that if Bucket were granted 5 minutes to communicate with the human world, she would look us straight in the eye, mumble ‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt ask to be born,‚Äù and then give us all the silent treatment for the remaining 4 minutes and 45 seconds.

One thing that is consistent is our trusty metal matriarch, Bertha, and her willingness to get us as far as we want to go. I am so very, very proud of my friend @katieboue as she launches @outdooradvocacy TODAY!
I would strongly encourage you to check out the website (in my bio for your convenience) and follow along on Instagram.
Katie has developed a one-stop-shop for all things advocacy. The website contains a full resource library ranging from everything to Public & Tribal Lands to Leave No Trace to current political bills, acts, proposals etc. that have an impact on the public lands we all love. You can even sign up with your email to be alerted on updates pertaining to certain bills and their statuses! You can also see a plethora of information on how to get involved, which was the driving force behind this creation of Katie‚Äôs.
So many of us want to help but we feel helpless. We don‚Äôt know where to go or what to do or who to call or where to donate. @outdooradvocacy hopes to change all of that. I‚Äôm so proud of my dear friend for pouring her heart into this and being the change üß°

This word is based off of occurrences/emotions throughout the year prior that could use a little attention or growth | When you choose a single word you have clarity and focus and room for movement as opposed to strict goals involving numbers or the possibility of that becoming ‚Äòbroken‚Äô or unattained | Do you set New Years resolutions? #2020 #happynewyear

‚ÄòYou workout on vacation!?‚Äô, ‚ÄòHow do you manage to stay fit while traveling?‚Äô, ‚ÄòHow do you stay motivated to workout when you‚Äôre away on a trip?‚Äô, ‚ÄòWhat are some tips for staying healthy while traveling?‚Äô Etc... the questions go on. Truth is I just love to workout and it‚Äôs part of the enjoyment in travel and vacationing for me - it sets the tone for the day. During the day we aren‚Äôt doing much, it‚Äôs been poolside/ocean side chillin‚Äô for the most part (though we did have a hiking day and walk the beach everyday), so getting up early and getting an hour or so workout in allows me to ‚Äòchill‚Äô for the rest of it - or else I may go crazy üòù. Being a runner makes it a bit easier to workout while traveling also, as all I need is my running shoes and some workout clothes and I am set. Over the years running has allowed me to explore the areas I travel to a lot easier where I am able to get in kms quicker. Body weight workouts and circuits are also common in my workout routine at home and on the go! I bought a skipping rope for this trip and it has been great as I do a ton of skipping at home and it‚Äôs easy to travel with ‚ù§Ô∏è | I also eat pretty well when I‚Äôm traveling as I have a sensitive stomach - so try to stay conscious of that (but trust me I indulge too) ‚ò∫Ô∏è I also walk everywhereeeee I can instead of using public transit - and I love my after dinner walks while away and at home - the kms add up! | The fact that Craig also values fitness makes it easier as we keep each other motivated when we are away from town, and at home #fitness #travel #freshairandfreedom

Be brave. Be kind. Be grateful | The locals said this was one of the best sunsets they‚Äôve had in months... lucky to have been able to witness it while enjoying a dinner on the beach üíõüå¥ This trip has gone by so quickly, heading home tomorrow evening and it‚Äôs back to work Monday morning!  #manzanillo #mexico #colima #iphonephoto #noedit #freshairandfreedom

At the end of last season I went on an incredible all women's sail-to-ski trip in northern Norway. We spent 11 days on the boat sailing through the Lyngen Alps, stopping each day to explore a new island. On our trip we only encountered two other women and only one other splitboarder. Which I thought was crazy üòù My community at home is so large and female dominated that I forget how small of a sport splitboarding is and how few women participate. So, in hopes of changing that, I gave my entire setup to a local snowboarder in Troms√∏. .

Just got back to the cold after a week in Hawaii with the @vans family for the duct tape festival. Every minute of my day this past week was filled with something fun ü§† surfing, backyard bbq‚Äôs, movie premieres, dinners, skate jams, art shows, live music, smoothies, sea turtles and conservation workshops. perPostData.comment: Everyday, I‚Äôm so glad he said yes. To all the ladies who are thinking about popping the question this engagement season, do it! There is nothing wrong with proposing to your man, for speaking up and asking for what you want. Only the insecure person is emasculated by a woman who speaks up and asks for what she wants. I can‚Äôt wait to celebrate our first Christmas as a married couple. Love you always @rob.lea. Photo: @erinorthcutt #climbforequality

Checking in with my bridesmaids on their dress color choices from Everest base camp was something I‚Äôll never forget. Thank goodness we had LTE there so we could pull off this mismatched but cohesive bridesmaids dress look. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Planning my wedding was so much fun! It was something I had been dreaming of for so long. ‚Å£
‚Å£
It happened at the perfect time in my life. It took me a long time to accept and love the part of myself that loves to wear dresses and twirl around in chiffon. It took me a long time to accept that I can be a feminist and want to be a bride and a wife. Gender equality is all about honoring the best parts of everyone. ‚Å£
‚Å£
I love these strong, brave and beautiful women! And strong is the new pretty! ‚Å£
#climbforequality ‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo: @erinorthcutt

This was one moment from 2019 that I‚Äôll never forget. I wanted to soak in every last moment of this sunset at Camp 2 on Everest/Chomolungma (25,000‚Äô/7620m), but my fingers could only handle a few moments of the cold before I had to zip up the tent and warm back up. Sharing that moment with my now husband, @rob.lea, was the greatest gift in the world. You‚Äôre officially off the hook for a Christmas present this year, Rob. 
#bigmtndreams #climbforequality

Merry Christmas! 
We woke up to a White Christmas at home in Utah and are so excited to spend our first holiday as Mr. and Mrs. with family, friends and on skis. Happy holidays from our family to yours! 
Photo: @leecohen_pics

‚ÄúOne can never be bored by powder skiing because it is a special gift of the relationship between earth and sky. It only comes in sufficient amounts in particular places, at certain times on this earth; it lasts only a limited amount of time before sun and wind changes it. People devote their whole lives to it for the pleasure of being so purely played by gravity and snow.‚Äù -Dolores LaChapelle 
@clifbar #CraftedwithPurpose @patagonia_snow

2019 was a big year. We bought a house. We started a foundation. I tore my ACL. I reached the highest point in the world. I had knee surgery. I crewed @rob.lea on his English Channel swim. I hiked up to the highest peak in the UK 6 weeks after knee surgery. We got married. I rode my bike almost a thousand miles with Rob and crewed him on his ride across America. I testified to the Senate about how climate change is affecting the mountains. I marched for climate. I shared my story with hundreds of people in real life in the many keynotes and talks I did. I took my nieces and nephews camping and taught them how to climb and ski.‚Å£
‚Å£
But perhaps what I‚Äôm most proud of in 2019 is learning how to love myself. I know that sounds clich√©, but hear me out. I used to approach skiing and mountaineering as an escape and a form of self punishment. I would always try to go a little harder and push myself to hurt a little more.  It was like a drug, a way of punishing my body and escaping my inner demons.‚Å£
‚Å£
It taken me a long time to work through that and come to a place where I approach what I do from a place of self love. To be able to stop when it hurts, to rest when I need it. To say no to those things that don‚Äôt serve me. Where it‚Äôs not about disciplining my body  but it‚Äôs about passion and love, for the places I‚Äôm in, for my partners and for myself. Here‚Äôs to more of that in 2020. Whatever we do in 2020, let‚Äôs do it from a place of love.

When I was a kid growing up in Minnesota, I used to struggle with overwhelming sadness during the winter months. I remember when I first learned about Seasonal Affective Depression, I felt a wave of relief. I finally had language to describe what I had been feeling. I also learned that skiing was a treatment. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Skiing and mountaineering have become a way of coping with depression. It‚Äôs a way of finding light in the darkness of my mind. It‚Äôs a way to survive the dark winter months. I thought I‚Äôd share this today on the winter solstice. After today, every day will get a little bit brighter. ‚Å£happy winter solstice to all my friends in the Northern Hemisphere. I‚Äôm so grateful to have a space here where I can talk about this stuff. Thanks for your kindness and compassion. ‚Å£
Photo: taking in the sunset from camp 3 at 27,000‚Äô on Everest/Chomolungma, a moment from 2019 that I‚Äôll never forget!

Asking my mom to be the officiant at our wedding had significance to me in so many ways. First, it was a celebration of our mother-daughter relationship that has grown with strength through the years! She knows me so well, and her open endorsement of my marriage was an important acknowledgement. Her example of partnership with my dad for more than 40 years is a representation of the power of marriage. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Secondly, it was a tribute to the times that embrace women in positions of power that previously had been deemed only for men. I grew up Catholic. Seeing the restrictions set on women in what they could do or not do sent a strong signal to me as a young person about a woman‚Äôs place. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Thirdly, it was so much fun to write the ceremony together! We were creative, imaginative and put together a meaningful ceremony to launch an important transition in my life! We were inspired by many different traditions and incorporated them into the ceremony. It was spiritual with a lot of humor, exactly the tone we wanted to set for our wedding. I am so grateful she took on the extra work of officiating. I couldn‚Äôt have imagined anyone else marrying us.‚Å£ I would highly recommend other people who are looking for an officiant to consider a family member! It is such a fun way to bond! 
Photo: @erinorthcutt

Today‚Äôs training: .75 miles up the snowy road towing Huck in the trailer. This workout is an incredible way to target hips and glutes. There are few gym exercises that give this same kind of burn. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Seriously, though, I have mad respect for all the parents out there. Getting outdoors with kids is like training for a Himalayan expedition! ‚Å£
‚Å£
If you don‚Äôt already follow @brooke.froelich, check her out. She‚Äôs one of my best friends and it‚Äôs been so inspiring to see her navigate motherhood and the outdoors. Serious #momgoals! Love ya Brooke! I‚Äôm so glad we‚Äôve stayed close and find creative ways to get outdoors together.

Climb up the mountain, ski down. I love the uphill experience, the gentle rhythm of moving through the mountains and being in the elements. It reminds me that I'm not separate from the earth but a part of it. And wind, snow and humidity are no match for my #JaybirdVista headphones. They can handle whatever I throw at them. Thanks to @jaybirdsport for powering this magical early season adventure. #earthproof

Today marks 7 months since I had ACL replacement surgery. To my fellow knee injury buddies, I thought I‚Äôd share some of what I‚Äôve learned in my recovery so far. ‚Å£Here are my top twelve:
‚Å£
1.  It‚Äôs ok to have moments of wallowing in self despair. Being depressed because you‚Äôre unable to do what you love is completely understandable. It takes time to find the silver lining with injuries. Or maybe you never find it. For those struggling, I see you. You‚Äôre not alone. It‚Äôs going to be ok.‚Å£ I‚Äôve found @headspace to be really useful during challenging times (unsponsored).
2.  Focus on what you can do, not what you can‚Äôt.‚Å£
3.  Remember all the ways it could be worse.‚Å£
4.  If you‚Äôve torn your ACL, find a physical therapist that you love because you‚Äôve going to be spending a lot of time together. Cherish each day of having a personal trainer and have fun with it! Grateful for you @smmurnin!
5.  Don‚Äôt compare yourself to your pre-injury state. Don‚Äôt compare yourself to others. Focus on doing the best you can everyday. (still struggle with this, not just with knee stuff)‚Å£
6.  Celebrate the little and big successes in your recovery.‚Å£
7.  Injuries create space for new growth and opportunities to do things you wouldn‚Äôt expect. Enjoy the unexpected. ‚Å£
8.  Stay connected to people by taking group fitness classes when you‚Äôre ready. Swim if you can‚Äôt weight bear (get a pull buoy so you just use your arms, not your legs). Also, follow @theaclclub.‚Å£
9.  I found reformer Pilates to be an awesome way to strengthen, stretch and re-learn how to balance when I was injured. 
10.  Try dry needling, kinesio tape and other recovery tools like @ntrecovery legs.‚Å£
11.  Try CBD for pain/discomfort and turmeric for swelling. For me, @gaiaherbs hemp products were a life-saver.‚Å£
12.  Try to get a little bit of sunshine each day, even if you‚Äôre on crutches. For me, the vitamin D is imperative to my mood. 
I‚Äôd love to hear your tips! Share in the comments below! 
@keen #keenambassador

Happy New Year‚Äôs Eve to you and happy birthday to me!‚Å£
‚Å£
My birthday wish is that everyone will realize the power we have to create the world we want to see and speak up on the issues that matter. I want to thank you for your support in disrupting implicit bias and creating a more equitable world. If you haven‚Äôt already, post and pledge to #climbforequality! Pledge to vote. And stay tuned for more info on a big action around climate change on January 31! #actonclimate ‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo: taking in the views from the roof of the world, camp 2 at 25,000‚Äô/ 7,620m on Everest/Chomolungma. Tearing my ACL seven weeks before Everest was one of my lowest lows. It‚Äôs still hard for me to believe I was able to complete the climb without my ACL. ‚Å£
‚Å£
It was such an incredible year where I had to confront my worst fears while accomplishing my biggest goals. I can‚Äôt wait for what‚Äôs ahead.

After our wedding, we jumped straight into the bike portion of Rob‚Äôs Ultimate World Tri and we never got to take a real honeymoon. ‚Å£
‚Å£
When @clubmedalpedhuez invited us to check out their newly renovated resort, we thought, why not take a mini-moon? I can think of few places more romantic than the Alps over the holidays. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Today, our luggage showed up after a 20-hour delay and we skied one of the longest in-bounds runs in Europe, about 6,000‚Äô vertical!‚Å£
It‚Äôs hard to comprehend the scale of the Alps. There are few runs in North America that are this long. ‚Å£
‚Å£
The views from the top and the excitement of the speed on the downhill burned off the jet leg and the knee felt good and strong today! Can‚Äôt wait to continue exploring tomorrow. ‚Å£

I moved to Utah with my family when I was 15. My first season, I skied in a rain jacket and sunglasses. I didn‚Äôt have goggles. I never had a new pair of skis until a sponsor gave them to me. ‚Å£
‚Å£
I learned how to ski when I was a kiddo, but I never raced or skied competitively growing up. I did take a few lessons and I cherished every one of them. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Snow sports can be incredibly difficult to get in to, especially as an adult. That‚Äôs one of the things I really appreciated about our stay at @clubmedalpedhuez. Their packages are a relatively affordable way to go skiing. ‚Å£
‚Å£
It can seem so overwhelming to go for a day of skiing, much less a ski vacation, sometimes I question whether it‚Äôs worth it. But at the end of the day, it‚Äôs experiences like these that we cherish more than any thing. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Happy mini-moon, @rob.lea. Here‚Äôs to our first few months of marriage.

Getting back into skiing this year after ACL surgery has been challenging. I‚Äôm just over six months out and some days, it feels like I‚Äôm taking two steps forward one step back. It‚Äôs been a slow process and my knee still feels like it‚Äôs 70%. ‚Å£
‚Å£
It gives me a ton of appreciation for the times in my life I‚Äôve been in peak fitness. And it makes skiing interesting again. I‚Äôm learning so many new ways to use my leg everyday. It excites and tires me. My brain is making new connections. My balance and proprioception are challenged. ‚Å£
‚Å£
I‚Äôm working my way back up slowly and conservatively and taking it one day at a time. And constantly telling my muscles and knee how strong and awesome they are! ‚Å£
‚Å£
Your body hears what you say to it and your cells and tissue react. What story are you telling your body? ‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo: @rob.lea

Stop buying things people don‚Äôt want use that money to save the planet by making a donation in their name (thanks for inspiring this caption, @ajabarber).‚Å£
‚Å£
The best gift you can give someone right now is a donation to an environmental non-profit through @patagonia Action Works. Patagonia will match all donations to environmental groups up to $10,000,000 from now until December 31! That‚Äôs right. $10 million. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Make a donation in someone‚Äôs name. There‚Äôs no better time to give. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Go to patagonia.com/actionworks to donate now and help save the planet. The earth needs you. ‚Å£
‚Å£
A few of my favorite orgs to give to:‚Å£
‚Å£
@healutah, @utahcleanenergy, @protectbearsears, @treeutah, @winterwildlandsalliance, @protectourwinters, @outdooralliance, @outdoorafro, @savethebwca and @latinooutdoors. There are so many good ones! Find your local non-profits and get involved. 
#AnswerWithAction

I‚Äôve been extremely fortunate that my skiing and climbing has taken me all over the world, opening my mind and my heart up to new people, places and perspectives I otherwise might not have experienced. It‚Äôs what truly makes me come alive. It‚Äôs instilled in me a fierce desire to not only protect these places where I play, but this planet that‚Äôs home to all of us.

It also comes with guilt. Guilt associated with the footprint my travels have that are unfortunately a consequence of doing what I love.

It‚Äôs no secret we live in an imperfect society and I, as is everyone, am an imperfect human. I am part of the problem. But I am also part of the solution. Which is why, despite this sometimes crippling guilt, I won‚Äôt hold myself back from speaking up and driving awareness and action on issues I care about.

With that said, I‚Äôm excited to share that @protectourwinters has a new carbon offset program. While, again, it‚Äôs not perfect, as in our carbon-based society it‚Äôs impossible to be, it is progress. And a great option I plan to embrace in my own travels going forward. Because what makes us come alive is exactly what the world needs right now.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
Hit the link below or in my bio to learn more about POW‚Äôs program.

https://carbon.protectourwinters.org/calculate
Photo @acpictures

After skiing with the family, we snuck out for a lap in the backcountry amidst the freshly coated Christmas trees. I‚Äôve spent a bunch of time this week teaching my nieces and nephews how to ski. My hope is that their memories of the time we spent together in nature will last long after they outgrow their toys. Time spent together outside is the best gift we can give each other. 
Photo: @rob.lea

One of the biggest highlights of my 2019 was meeting @mrapinoe, @gloriasteinem and @hollylawrencetri at the the @clifbar HQ.‚Å£

I used to approach skiing and mountaineering as an escape and a form of self punishment. I would always try to go a little harder and push myself to hurt a little more. Today marks 7 months since I had ACL replacement surgery. To my fellow knee injury buddies, I thought I‚Äôd share some of what I‚Äôve learned in my recovery so far. ‚Å£Here are my top twelve:
‚Å£
1.  It‚Äôs ok to have moments of wallowing in self despair. Being depressed because you‚Äôre unable to do what you love is completely understandable. It takes time to find the silver lining with injuries. Or maybe you never find it. For those struggling, I see you. You‚Äôre not alone. It‚Äôs going to be ok.‚Å£ I‚Äôve found @headspace to be really useful during challenging times (unsponsored).
2.  Focus on what you can do, not what you can‚Äôt.‚Å£
3.  Remember all the ways it could be worse.‚Å£
4.  If you‚Äôve torn your ACL, find a physical therapist that you love because you‚Äôve going to be spending a lot of time together. Cherish each day of having a personal trainer and have fun with it! Grateful for you @smmurnin!
5.  Don‚Äôt compare yourself to your pre-injury state. Don‚Äôt compare yourself to others. Focus on doing the best you can everyday. (still struggle with this, not just with knee stuff)‚Å£
6.  Celebrate the little and big successes in your recovery.‚Å£
7.  Injuries create space for new growth and opportunities to do things you wouldn‚Äôt expect. Enjoy the unexpected. ‚Å£
8.  Stay connected to people by taking group fitness classes when you‚Äôre ready. Swim if you can‚Äôt weight bear (get a pull buoy so you just use your arms, not your legs). Also, follow @theaclclub.‚Å£
9.  I found reformer Pilates to be an awesome way to strengthen, stretch and re-learn how to balance when I was injured. 
10.  Try dry needling, kinesio tape and other recovery tools like @ntrecovery legs.‚Å£
11.  Try CBD for pain/discomfort and turmeric for swelling. For me, @gaiaherbs hemp products were a life-saver.‚Å£
12.  Try to get a little bit of sunshine each day, even if you‚Äôre on crutches. For me, the vitamin D is imperative to my mood. 
I‚Äôd love to hear your tips! Share in the comments below!

Oh hayyyyyy everyone! It‚Äôs been a while. After getting back to Arizona, I decided to give myself a good 2 weeks to relax - something I haven‚Äôt done in a long time. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
I love my job and sharing the world through my eyes with you all, but something I need to get better at is knowing when to shut down. I‚Äôm all about hard work, but I don‚Äôt necessarily believe working longer means you‚Äôre working smarter or ‚Äúharder‚Äù. And after reflecting on my 2019, I didn‚Äôt realize how much working longer hours kept me from enjoying myself at times. BUT I‚Äôm other news, 2019 was a great year. Here‚Äôs a quick run down of what it looked like for me:‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚ú®Scott and I moved into a campervan! We got rid of all our belongings and left our apartment in April‚†Ä
‚ú®Leaving from Arizona, we traveled to Utah, California, Washington, Oregon, Montana, Wyoming, Idaho, just about all of New England, North & South Carolina, South Dakota, Ohio, then back to AZ‚†Ä
‚ú®I exceeded the financial goals I had for my business which was a major win‚†Ä
‚ú®I forced myself to start learning video, something I‚Äôm looking forward to in 2020‚†Ä
‚ú®I was able to work with 90% of my dream clients on projects I‚Äôm proud of‚†Ä
‚ú®I was able to get my acne under control (something I‚Äôve struggled with in the past) and learned how to maintain a healthy diet/ exercise routine while traveling (something else I put off most times)‚†Ä
‚†Ä
All in all, it was a great year! I genuinely hope yours was too and 2020 is even better‚ò∫Ô∏è. What are some things you‚Äôre looking forward to this year? Let me know in the comments!‚†Ä

TIPS FOR VISITING HOT SPRINGSüåû‚ùÑÔ∏èüëáüèº‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Winter is riiiiiight around the corner and IDK about you, but I have every intention of finding some hot springs to soak in. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Before you take a dip in a hot spring this season, whether it's in California, Oregon, Idaho, or elsewhere, keep these tips in mind! ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
*ùó¶ùóÆùòÉùó≤ ùòÅùóµùó∂ùòÄ ùóΩùóºùòÄùòÅ ùó≥ùóºùóø ùó≥ùòÇùòÅùòÇùóøùó≤ ùóµùóºùòÅ ùòÄùóΩùóøùó∂ùóªùó¥ ùòÅùóøùó∂ùóΩ ùóΩùóπùóÆùóªùóªùó∂ùóªùó¥*‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
1. Snag yourself some hiking sandals like Chacos! I can't tell you how many times I slipped and slide through some hot springs. LOL. The surface below the spring is a lot slicker than you might think! Hiking sandals will give you some traction and prevent slipping. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
2. Drink Water - Believe it or not, if you choose to skip out on hydrating, you run the risk of heatstroke! Make sure you bring a reusable water bottle with you and hydrate as much as possible! Keep glass containers away from hot springs. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
3. Test The Water - Ohhhhh lawdy. I swear, there were some hot springs in Idaho that I'm pretty sure would have singed my skin right off LMAO. Before getting into a spring, test the water! Doing so might prevent you from getting into a spring that's not that warm in the first place. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
4. The Warmest Water Is Closest To The Source - It's usually pretty easy to spot the source of hot spring water. Sometimes folks lead it to a pool with a PVC pipe. Therefore, the closer you are to the source, the warmer the water will be!‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
5. Save The Bath For Home - Hot Springs aren't a bathtub! Soaps (even the natural kind) can severely damage a spring and cause it to cool down over time. You also run the risk at smelling like sulfur/ farts, so just save the bath for when you get home lol. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Want more tips and details about the best hot springs?‚Å†‚†Ä
‚†Ä
ùóñùóµùó≤ùó∞ùó∏ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùóπùó∂ùóªùó∏ ùó∂ùóª ùó∫ùòÜ ùóØùó∂ùóº! I've written up blogs about the best Idaho hot springs as well as some awesome hot springs you can enjoy in California! Give the blogs a read and start planning your next hot spring getaway!

AD | Does anyone else remember when my Instagram was hacked earlier this year? When that happened, I questioned how I‚Äôm supposed to keep my information safe considering my entire life is showcased on the internet. My privacy + security are important to me!‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm SO ecstatic to be partnering with @Avast to raise awareness of the importance of adding more security into your life! Avast is dedicated to making users feel safe online, using their technologies to fight cyber attacks, which is why I use their mobile app and desktop service. Here‚Äôs some things I love about the premium version of the Avast mobile app:‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
‚úîÔ∏èI can turn on protection modes for my browser so my information is secure while paying bills‚Å†‚†Ä
‚úîÔ∏èTheir ‚ÄúPhoto Vault‚Äù allows me to set a passcode to access my images‚Å†‚†Ä
‚úîÔ∏è@avast has identity protection that alerts me if something fishy is going on with my passwords.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
So whether I‚Äôm out on an adventure or taking in an epic sunset, I can sit back and relax knowing my cyber-life is taken care of- one less thing I have to worry about. You can learn more about them in my story! #avast #freetoexplore

For the holiday gifting this year, I‚Äôve partnered with @REI! Before I get into all the good stuffüéÑ...‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
there are some things you should know about Scott and me.‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Believe it or not, everything in our van is everything we own! We like living with less, which is actually what makes holiday gifting for us such a pain point for our familiesüòÇ. You see, in our apartment, we slowlllyyy became collectors, especially with outdoor gear. I‚Äôm talking multiple backpacks, jackets galore, mismatching trekking poles. Eventually, we finally decided enough was enough, donated everything we could, and replaced what we needed to. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Now, a majority of our gear is made by companies doing some awesome things for the planet. Think products made from responsibly sourced materials, ethical supply chains, fair trade policies, etc. That‚Äôs because when we decided to live with just the essentials, we also decided that anything we do ‚Äúcollect‚Äù shouldn‚Äôt harm the planet. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
When considering what gifts to get outdoor lovers in your life, I highly recommend going eco-friendly! So many sustainable products out there are built to last and can be used for years to come. Plussss, Mother Nature will thank you! ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
You can read my round-up of eco-friendly gifts in collab with @REI by clicking the link in my bio! My Eco-Friendly Gift Guide for Outdoor Lovers includes gifts for him, her, and under $50. I‚Äôve also updated the guide to include some fantastic @REI classes you can gift and information about REI‚ÄôS Used Gear program that you can use for shopping too. Head to the link in my bio to check it out!üéÑüåé‚ú®

TIPS FOR VISITING HOT SPRINGSüåû‚ùÑÔ∏èüëáüèº‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Winter is riiiiiight around the corner and IDK about you, but I have every intention of finding some hot springs to soak in. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Before you take a dip in a hot spring this season, whether it's in California, Oregon, Idaho, or elsewhere, keep these tips in mind! ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
*ùó¶ùóÆùòÉùó≤ ùòÅùóµùó∂ùòÄ ùóΩùóºùòÄùòÅ ùó≥ùóºùóø ùó≥ùòÇùòÅùòÇùóøùó≤ ùóµùóºùòÅ ùòÄùóΩùóøùó∂ùóªùó¥ ùòÅùóøùó∂ùóΩ ùóΩùóπùóÆùóªùóªùó∂ùóªùó¥*‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
1. Snag yourself some hiking sandals like Chacos! I can't tell you how many times I slipped and slide through some hot springs. LOL. The surface below the spring is a lot slicker than you might think! Hiking sandals will give you some traction and prevent slipping. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
2. Drink Water - Believe it or not, if you choose to skip out on hydrating, you run the risk of heatstroke! Make sure you bring a reusable water bottle with you and hydrate as much as possible! Keep glass containers away from hot springs. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
3. Test The Water - Ohhhhh lawdy. I swear, there were some hot springs in Idaho that I'm pretty sure would have singed my skin right off LMAO. Before getting into a spring, test the water! Doing so might prevent you from getting into a spring that's not that warm in the first place. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
4. The Warmest Water Is Closest To The Source - It's usually pretty easy to spot the source of hot spring water. Sometimes folks lead it to a pool with a PVC pipe. Therefore, the closer you are to the source, the warmer the water will be!‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
5. Save The Bath For Home - Hot Springs aren't a bathtub! Soaps (even the natural kind) can severely damage a spring and cause it to cool down over time. You also run the risk at smelling like sulfur/ farts, so just save the bath for when you get home lol. ‚Å†‚†Ä
‚Å†‚†Ä
Want more tips and details about the best hot springs?‚Å†‚†Ä
‚†Ä
ùóñùóµùó≤ùó∞ùó∏ ùòÅùóµùó≤ ùóπùó∂ùóªùó∏ ùó∂ùóª ùó∫ùòÜ ùóØùó∂ùóº! I've written up blogs about the best Idaho hot springs as well as some awesome hot springs you can enjoy in California! Give the blogs a read and start planning your next hot spring getaway!

Oh hayyyyyy everyone! It‚Äôs been a while. After getting back to Arizona, I decided to give myself a good 2 weeks to relax - something I haven‚Äôt done in a long time. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
I love my job and sharing the world through my eyes with you all, but something I need to get better at is knowing when to shut down. I‚Äôm all about hard work, but I don‚Äôt necessarily believe working longer means you‚Äôre working smarter or ‚Äúharder‚Äù. And after reflecting on my 2019, I didn‚Äôt realize how much working longer hours kept me from enjoying myself at times. BUT I‚Äôm other news, 2019 was a great year. Here‚Äôs a quick run down of what it looked like for me:‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚ú®Scott and I moved into a campervan! We got rid of all our belongings and left our apartment in April‚†Ä
‚ú®Leaving from Arizona, we traveled to Utah, California, Washington, Oregon, Montana, Wyoming, Idaho, just about all of New England, North & South Carolina, South Dakota, Ohio, then back to AZ‚†Ä
‚ú®I exceeded the financial goals I had for my business which was a major win‚†Ä
‚ú®I forced myself to start learning video, something I‚Äôm looking forward to in 2020‚†Ä
‚ú®I was able to work with 90% of my dream clients on projects I‚Äôm proud of‚†Ä
‚ú®I was able to get my acne under control (something I‚Äôve struggled with in the past) and learned how to maintain a healthy diet/ exercise routine while traveling (something else I put off most times)‚†Ä
‚†Ä
All in all, it was a great year! I genuinely hope yours was too and 2020 is even better‚ò∫Ô∏è. What are some things you‚Äôre looking forward to this year? Let me know in the comments!‚†Ä

perPostData.comment: Spending the last weekend at @fivepinelodge spoiling myself and the dogs was absolutely the best way to finish the year. We sat in the most peaceful setting in a cozy cabin, watched wildlife, went for a couple walks in the forest, enjoyed some wine, finally got to take a v. luxurious bath + woke up to room service with fresh fruit, granola + local coffee. It feels so good to treat yourself + this was a great reminder that I need to do this more often. #FivePineLodge

Honestly, I go through waves of feeling super happy and feeling down. I don‚Äôt mean to mislead anyone on here, but I do hope that the photos I post and the stories I tell do make you happy & feel good. Right now though, I‚Äôm a bit down. A combination of an insane travel month last month that ended in me getting violently ill, overworking myself, overpromising things, and simply not enough down & me time. Mexico was more taxing on me than I think I even realize, but it sparked my desire to help more. Volunteering my time when and where I can is incredibly rewarding. It also means that I am giving away more time from myself and my family that I too, desperately need. Finding a balance is something I‚Äôve always struggled with... leaning too far any direction. I‚Äôm learning though. Learning to ask for help when I need it, learning when to say no.. and yes, learning to stand up for myself and speak my truth. Staying strong when life beats you down is incredibly difficult, and while stuff has been much harder than it is right now, it doesn‚Äôt matter or compare. Every little bit of hurt is still hurt now matter how big of a deal it may look or feel to someone else. Right now, I‚Äôm giving myself a break and saying no to most things... with the exception of time with my dogs. I hope you all take care of yourself this way too, put yourself first, always. ü§ç

I‚Äôve been meaning to write about this for sometime now, but just getting around to it... Finances! I started off 2019 in an absolute mess and a really bad spot... a bad financial place that I had been stuck in for about 3 years. With the guidance and some suggestions from my dad (thanks dad!), I can tell you right now that I‚Äôve never been more at peace and felt as stable before. While everyones journey to getting to a place where you‚Äôre feeling good is going to be different, I wanted to share some simple tips I learned and implemented that can help you too! 
The very first thing you can do today is to write out... yes, on pen and paper... your income versus expenses. Your income number should be the amount you get in your bank account after taxes AND after setting aside at least 10% of that paycheck into a retirement account. I set aside 18% because it‚Äôs easier to be aggressive now when I still have time on my side... not when I‚Äôm 50. Also, compound interest folks. For your expenses column, list it all.. everything you are spending money on. My expenses column also include a personal emergency savings account and a dog emergency savings account. When you compare the two columns... the goal here is to have your income still higher than your expenses. If it‚Äôs not... time to do some adjusting. Where can you cut out expenses? Food, yard maintenance, clothing? The only way to get out of the negative is to tighten those budgets up! For me... for many, many months, I ate meals of pasta, rice, cereal, etc. I know it‚Äôs not the ‚Äòhealthiest‚Äô, but I was able to cut down on grocery bills tremendously just by altering a few meals. 
Finances don‚Äôt have to be scary and overwhelming... and certainly doesn‚Äôt require that trigonometry class you had to take in high school. You can do this. Looking forward to continuing to work towards a more financially healthy future in this new year, as I will be sitting down today and making more goals.
Heading into 2020 üòç

Spending a few days in the Sun Valley area with my sister right now! We‚Äôve decided that it‚Äôs important to get away, just the two of us, every year, even for just for a few days. 
Today was so much fun! We hit the slopes, and while it wasn‚Äôt totally sunny, the groomers were ripping, the air was cold & crisp and we had a blast! We followed up our chilly mountain time with some yoga & hot tubbing to warm up. 
Today, i‚Äôm grateful for the many gorgeous places, like Sun Valley, where we can get outside to play. 
@TravelMindset #seeksunvalley

Our final day in Sun Valley left us with a full heart and big grins. We headed into the Sawtooth National Forest via snowmobile with @sunvalleyguides, then we walked uphill to find some turns through this burn area. There‚Äôs something so beautiful and peaceful about skiing in a burn... maybe it‚Äôs the heavy contrasted environment, the creaking of the trees, the views, or the way the wind whips through and blows snow across the surface. It‚Äôs probably all of that and more. What a great way to end our trip + looking forward to coming back for more. Thank you @travelmindset for hosting this incredibly special trip for my sister and I ü§ç #seeksunvalley
