Waiting for the sun to rise to warm us up. Love a good winter hut camp üòå
@hydroflask #heyletsgo

@jennahstillman and I are on the same page in regards to how large of a pack we carry and how much important stuff goes inside of it... even if it‚Äôs only for a night or two. Those essentials include many cans of beer, whiskey, a fishing rod, face masks, camera, lenses, and lots of food, deserts + snacks. Jenna his the only other gal I know who also backpacks with a full 75L pack. Large + heavy packers where you at!? üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
@hydroflask #HeyLetsGo

Honestly, I go through waves of feeling super happy and feeling down. I don‚Äôt mean to mislead anyone on here, but I do hope that the photos I post and the stories I tell do make you happy & feel good. Right now though, I‚Äôm a bit down. A combination of an insane travel month last month that ended in me getting violently ill, overworking myself, overpromising things, and simply not enough down & me time. Mexico was more taxing on me than I think I even realize, but it sparked my desire to help more. Volunteering my time when and where I can is incredibly rewarding. It also means that I am giving away more time from myself and my family that I too, desperately need. Finding a balance is something I‚Äôve always struggled with... leaning too far any direction. I‚Äôm learning though. Learning to ask for help when I need it, learning when to say no.. and yes, learning to stand up for myself and speak my truth. Staying strong when life beats you down is incredibly difficult, and while stuff has been much harder than it is right now, it doesn‚Äôt matter or compare. Every little bit of hurt is still hurt now matter how big of a deal it may look or feel to someone else. Right now, I‚Äôm giving myself a break and saying no to most things... with the exception of time with my dogs. I hope you all take care of yourself this way too, put yourself first, always. ü§ç

Baya, my heart dog. I love absolutely everything about you. Words fall short when I try to explain how I feel about you, it simply is never enough to just say ‚ÄòI love you so much‚Äô. Thank you for overflowing my heart with joy & keeping me in check. Finding you wasn‚Äôt on my foreseen path. A bad turn of events left me shattered, and I am forever grateful for it. You‚Äôre the best thing that‚Äôs ever happened to me.  #HeartDog
Photo @jennahstillman

As Rio gets older, our adventure dates look a little different. He has pretty severe arthritis, so long trips on foot aren‚Äôt really an option for him anymore, so we‚Äôve started doing a lot more on the road and finding fun cabins to stay at. We can go on micro adventures, snuggle beside a fire, play games + eat good food. It‚Äôs essentially the same as it was before, something we all love to do together + but this is easier for him. For us, it‚Äôs simply about being together... at home, the outdoors or a cabin in a new place. 
@Backcountry believes anyone is capable of enjoying outdoor experiences, big or small, near or far ‚Äî to inspire people to have their best experiences outside recreating and enjoying open spaces, trying new adventurous activities, and really connecting with nature in a positive and meaningful way. 
I am partnering with @backcountry to keep encouraging you to get outside and find your backcountry, wherever that may be. Use code MTNPUPS for 15% off your first purchase at Backcountry.com! Exclusions apply. #sponsored #FindYourBackcountry

See my story for some of my favorite cabin getaway items!

Photo @jennahstillman
Jingle all the way ‚òÉÔ∏è

An excellent start to the ski season! The storms may have taken a little longer than were used to to show up, but they did, and they did well. Warmed up the legs on some beautiful, soft corduroy with my dad + soaked in some sunshine between some moody clouds. So happy to be back in this winter wonderland ü§ç #Outplay365 @mtbachelor
The cutest little snow boop üòç

Spending a few days in the Sun Valley area with my sister right now! We‚Äôve decided that it‚Äôs important to get away, just the two of us, every year, even for just for a few days. 
Today was so much fun! We hit the slopes, and while it wasn‚Äôt totally sunny, the groomers were ripping, the air was cold & crisp and we had a blast! We followed up our chilly mountain time with some yoga & hot tubbing to warm up. 
Today, i‚Äôm grateful for the many gorgeous places, like Sun Valley, where we can get outside to play. 
@TravelMindset #seeksunvalley

Our final day in Sun Valley left us with a full heart and big grins. We headed into the Sawtooth National Forest via snowmobile with @sunvalleyguides, then we walked uphill to find some turns through this burn area. There‚Äôs something so beautiful and peaceful about skiing in a burn... maybe it‚Äôs the heavy contrasted environment, the creaking of the trees, the views, or the way the wind whips through and blows snow across the surface. It‚Äôs probably all of that and more. What a great way to end our trip + looking forward to coming back for more. Thank you @travelmindset for hosting this incredibly special trip for my sister and I ü§ç #seeksunvalley

#ad As they say... sharing is caring! And there are good reasons why my dogs are always trying to get in on my bag of @KettleBrand chips! (Sorry @mtnpups, these are all mine).They're totally delicious & we love that they are always working towards improving their environmental footprint, encouraging others to do the same. Kettle Brand turns their spent oil into biodiesel and run their company car on it, and they integrate renewable energy into their operations, including the generation & use of solar & wind energy as well as water reclamation systems. Kettle Brand also is restoring the native landscape around their facilities, committing to protecting pollinators, and give more than 55,000 pounds of potatoes to hunger relief agencies & and chips to schools and local organizations. Thank you, @KettleBrand, for being so environmentally conscious! #LiveFlavorfully

Wishing you all the very best this holiday season & the happiest of New Years. I‚Äôm grateful for all of you who follow us here and looking forward to making many more memories next year. Here‚Äôs to many miles covered with my dogs at my side, another year older, a new addition to the family (lil‚Äô Sage), getting completely out of *massive* debt and helping dogs in Mexico, to name a few of my favorite moments. What will be in store for us next year? Whatever it is, I‚Äôm sure it will be great ü§ç

Been doing some snow dances in hopes Ullr will deliver soon üôèüèº‚òÉÔ∏è
@mtbachelor #OutPlay365

Spending the last weekend at @fivepinelodge spoiling myself and the dogs was absolutely the best way to finish the year. We sat in the most peaceful setting in a cozy cabin, watched wildlife, went for a couple walks in the forest, enjoyed some wine, finally got to take a v. luxurious bath + woke up to room service with fresh fruit, granola + local coffee. It feels so good to treat yourself + this was a great reminder that I need to do this more often. #FivePineLodge

What a ride this decade has been. Ten years ago I had no animals and was working for my parents in their dental office. Several career changes in between, 5 animals acquired, a house purchased, debt grown to $80k+ and paid off (in this year!), relationships grown and lost and so much learning and growing. I‚Äôm so happy with all the changes, even if they hurt like hell and I didn‚Äôt like them at the time. I‚Äôm thankful for it all. Looking forward to more change, more memories made and more animals acquired (jkjkjk I‚Äôm not THAT crazy...üòè). Here‚Äôs to you, to 2020, and to keepin‚Äô it real, no matter what.
Wishing you an amazing new year from my little family to yours ‚ú® #OneSecondEveryday

A few weeks ago a friend of mine made a comment about how my social media was a decent representation of who I am but was lacking depth. I‚Äôve always been sensitive to the fact that it‚Äôs easy to be perceived as vain on an app like this and that sharing too much personal information can be kinda scary. I guess I maybe thought that people just like to see nice photos and don‚Äôt really care to know too much about the person behind the screen. After our chat I figured for anyone who might not know me personally and maybe does want a little more insight on that blonde girl who pops up on their Instagram feed from time to time I‚Äôd share a few things about myself.
1. I‚Äôm 25 years old
2. I live in Whistler, BC but I‚Äôm from Ottawa, ON
3. I love to ski, workout, bike, surf and hike
4. I‚Äôm currently self employed and make most of my income from social media but also do some consulting work and the odd modelling job 
5. I hate the word ‚Äòslice‚Äô, arrogant people and the sound of airplane toilets 
6. I‚Äôm extremely afraid of snakes and heights
7. My favorite thing to eat is a taco and my favorite thing to drink is a passionfruit margarita
8. I have exceptionally ugly feet
9. I‚Äôm one of five kids 
10. My pet peeves are when people use plastic straws or when people don‚Äôt say thank you
11. A few of my life goals are to become a personal trainer, buy myself a house, live in a different country, go up in a hot air balloon, speak three languages and own a golden retriever puppy
12. My favorite book is The Alchemist, my favorite movie is ‚ÄòStand By Me‚Äô and my favorite song is Skinny Love by Bon Iver 
13. I love getting mail more than just about anything
14. I also love road trips, sunshine, chocolate covered almonds and people who make me laugh
15. Besides Canada - Mexico, Morocco and Austria are my favorite places in the world
16. I like buying my clothes from thrift stores cause that way I don‚Äôt have the same things as anyone else
17. My middle name is Quinte..
18. I can touch my tongue to my nose and I sometimes I clap when a plane lands smoothly.
‚Ä¢
If you know me and can think of anything else feel free to comment below but I think I covered just about everything üí´
I‚Äôm home and it‚Äôs snowing and I slept in my own bed last night and I got invited to a chritsmas party and my family is coming to visit me for the holidays and everything is wonderful üí´

Joined the quarter century club today. I‚Äôm not gonna lie, 24 was an interesting year. Excited and looking forward to whatever‚Äôs next üí´Thank you all so much for the birthday wishes- now time to go drink too many margaritas and dance all night üíõ

I decided to come to Mexico for an open ended period of time this fall. I‚Äôve done my fair share of travelling throughout the last few years- ticking a lot of places off the map but rarely ever allowing myself to slow down long enough to just be somewhere. 
This country is really special to me and my goal this time around was to connect with it a little deeper, explore some new places and make sure that my time here wasn‚Äôt some big rush. To appreciate the art, listen to the music, go to the museums, eat the food, understand the architecture, embrace the history, walk the streets, surf the waves, visit the big cities, lay on the beaches, and make friends with the people. To be a traveller, not a tourist. A few months ago I signed up for the @cibc Aventura Visa Infinite Card - the extra points that I earned when signing up for the card were put towards getting down here and travelling in and around this big and beautifully diverse country. They were put towards leaving the beach to go explore a city (something I wouldn‚Äôt normally do) - to finding the most beautiful hot springs and the best tacos- to realizing Mexico does in fact have some mountains and that my new favourite dessert is a churro. They were put towards giving this place a little more depth and meaning for me üíõ‚Ä®‚Ä¢‚Ä®Click the link in my bio to sign up for the @CIBC Aventura Visa Infinite Card today and earn 35,000 points - that‚Äôs up to $800 towards your next flight. Here‚Äôs hoping you‚Äôll use them to go and explore somewhere new or maybe to connect deeper with somewhere you‚Äôve already been like I have these past few weeks with Mexico üí´#CIBCAventura #sponsored
Home away from home @casadelaballena üå∏üêãüíõ
Sagittarius season üòàüí´‚ôêÔ∏èüåô

Sipping on coconuts, playing in the waves, laying in the sun, hugging friends, walking everywhere barefoot, feeling the sand between my toes, the salt on my skin, the hot sticky wind through my hair and an over flow of love, calmness, joy and belonging in my heart. When I close my eyes and think of paradise it looks and feels a little something like this üå∏ I love it here. #35mm
Let‚Äôs goooooo üí´ @whistlerblackcomb

‚ÄòTo invest in travel is to invest in yourself‚Äô ü¶ã I‚Äôve made a solid point over the past few years to invest a lot of my time, energy and money into seeing the world. I‚Äôve always thought of it as the best way to get to know myself and grow as a human being. To figure out the places that make me the happiest, the people who make me better and the activities that make me feel the most alive by putting myself in  new and unfamiliar environments. But travelling, especially as a young female, can be a bit intimidating at times. I‚Äôve learnt over the past few years that having a solid credit card with perks that fit my lifestyle has eliminated a lot of extra stress while out on the road. It's made it easier to track my spending, it's protected me from theft and it‚Äôs helped me enjoy my time out exploring the world just a little bit more.
‚Ä¢
I discovered the @cibc Aventura Visa Infinite Card about a year ago. The points I earned from applying for the card and using it frequently over the last 12 months helped me get down to Mexico this fall, relax, and really give surfing a go. Some of the card‚Äôs other perks include 4 complimentary airport lounge visits per year, mobile device insurance and I even got a rebate on my Nexus Application Fee. Not to mention the ‚Äòhotel burglary insurance‚Äô attached to the card helped me get through a pretty tough time when I got robbed down in Costa Rica 6 months ago.
‚Ä¢
So if you enjoy seeing the world as much as I do, and are looking for a new travel card - invest in yourself by clicking the link in my bio and signing up for the CIBC Aventura Visa Infinite Card today üí´ Happy travels #CIBCAventura #sponsored
Dreamin üí´

Yesterdays sunrise from the far end of Little Cottonwood Canyon üí´ Wrapping up an awesome week of skiing, shooting and spa-ing in Utah with an all time crew. Couldn‚Äôt dream up a better way to start the winter üíõ @backcountry #bananaspliff
Adios 24 üí´

I made a promise to myself this year that I would slow down and spend more time at home. Being in a mountain town during the slow season can drive people a little stir crazy. This fall I decided to stay home for a good portion of it but also made a pact that I wasn‚Äôt going to be one of those people. I tried to fill my days with things that would keep me busy and active before the snow started to fall. Another thing I promised myself this year was to start trying new things regardless of how bad I just might be at them in the beginning. I‚Äôve always had a hard time being the worst at something which in hindsight has probably robbed me from a lot of beautiful experiences. With that said- one of the best decisions I made in 2019 was to finally get myself a mountain bike. To give myself a gift that allows me to experience and explore my beautiful home with fresh eyes and have something new to work on and improve at.  Big thanks my friends @backcountry for helping me pick out a bike, for getting me set up with all of the proper equipment and for always, always, always encouraging me to get outside and try new things üíõ
‚Ä¢

2020 ! The start of a new year and a new decade üí´ I ate about 700 pieces of chocolate over the holidays (not even an exaggeration) so it‚Äôs time to start setting goals, eating healthy and getting back in shape. Wandering among the treetops, glittered with lights. I've been dreaming of these PNW vibes for so long ‚ú®
‚Ä¢
Wearing @eddiebauer's Bygone 25 Pack #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor

My top 5 photos of 2019 countdown continued!

Photo 2: Faraway Fantasy

Traveling across China for a month was my biggest personal project of the year. In 2017, sitting at my desk at my day job, I stumbled onto a Chinese tourism website for the province of Guizhou that looked like it was made in 1995, with tiny pixelated thumbnail images of some of the most insane landscapes I had never seen before. Right there and then, I knew I needed to find a way there someday. 
Fast forward to this August and, although it was my biggest travel challenge yet to navigate China, I was finally there and getting to take the photos I‚Äôd had in my head for so long. When we arrived at this Bavarian-looking castle (discovered via a deep Pinterest search session), I had only ever seen photos from the front, so I was surprised to discover these insane mountains were behind it too.

We were exploring around the castle when I realized the sun was dipping beneath the peaks, so I literally sprinted to a spot I could launch the drone from before all the light was gone. When I saw these light rays on my screen, I almost cried from relief that all the travel difficulties and money I‚Äôd thrown into this trip were paying off. An image several years in the making.

Would you travel a solid 48 hours one way just to see this mountainside temple in person? 
It took us a ridiculous amount of trains, buses, taxis and cable cars to get us here. But I don‚Äôt regret a single second of it.
Wishing you a very happy holiday season from Santa‚Äôs little helpers üéÖüèªüéÑüòú Photo collab with: @lizah & @errincasa ‚ú®
Light rays along the Oregon coast. Excited to be back exploring this beautiful state in a couple days ‚ú®

Turquoise tiers of hot spring pools hidden in the middle of a giant forest. This gem was the perfect place to spend a moody, rainy day relaxing. I think I could get used to this PNW lifestyle.

Photo by @errincasa / my edit

Continuing my top five favorite photos of 2019 countdown!

Photo 4: Jurassic Jungle

The most challenging thing about traveling East Java, Indonesia is the inevitable sleep deprivation. Every spot you want to see is hours away from each other, and almost all require hikes in the dark before sunrise, so we pulled several all nighters that week.

On our last morning of this insane schedule, we did a three hour drive starting at 3am in order to make it to this waterfall for sunrise. When we got to the top of the falls, I sent the drone up and realized just how worth it the send was. Not only was I able to capture the low hanging fog before it burned off for the day, but the volcano in the distance was glowing slightly pink, kind of like you‚Äôd see alpenglow in the mountains.

I‚Äôve found that the trips that push me the hardest mentally and physically usually end up not only being the most memorable, but produce my best work. It‚Äôs Type 2 kind of fun, but this photo and particular trip were definitely a testament to that.

Walking through Petra really does feel like you‚Äôre being transported to an entirely different time and place. At the end of each day when we walked back out into the real world, emerging from the ancient city, it was like snapping back out of some sort of magic this place holds.

Photo by @mikesugianto / my edit

Can you believe this natural Turkish hot spring is over 2,000 years old? Now a UNESCO World Heritage site,  it‚Äôs Turkish name directly translates to Cotton Castle. We had a fun morning running around, exploring every single pool. On our road trip around the country, we discovered Turkey is full of ancient gems like this one.

Photos by @mikesugianto / my edits

I‚Äôm spending the last five days of the year counting down my favorite photos from 2019, and sharing more BTS on what it took to get the shot!

Photo 5: Desert Dweller

We had been camping in Wadi Rum for a couple days, which was highly unusual for tourists because it got to 105 during the day and, stuck in the desert without A/C, I swear I thought I was starting to hallucinate.

But then golden hour finally came around and we convinced the son of the camp owner to drive us around in the back of his truck. I was hoping for a shot with camels in the background, and luckily this curious camel decided to walk right up to us. The scarf I‚Äôm wearing is called a Keffiyeh, which Jordanian desert nomads wear to protect their head from the sun and their face from sand (they happily tied it on for me). When I saw the preview of this image in the back of @mikesugianto‚Äôs camera, I was beyond stoked we managed to capture all these unique local elements in a single photo and in golden light. I knew immediately it would be my favorite shot from the whole trip.

I‚Äôve been a total hermit at home the past couple days, staying up til 3am working on getting the Live Your Dreams Workshop ready to launch Monday morning (if you don‚Äôt know what I‚Äôm talking about, check out the ‚ÄúWorkshop‚Äù story highlight on my profile!). Confession: I have not put on real pants in over 48 hours and have been surviving solely off of hummus and la croix LOL glamorous, I know. 
So here‚Äôs a throwback to this gorgeous hike in Zion with the best 360 views. Very much looking forward to getting some fresh air and stretching my legs on a hike soon.

Photos of me by @mikesugianto / my edits
Always and forever chasing light rays ‚ú®

This turned out to be one of my favorite adventures of the year, canyoneering up river, swimming and bouldering to reach a waterfall at the end of the canyon. Afterwards, we got to float most of the way back, looking straight up at these red rock walls. All I‚Äôm left wondering is how exactly this boulder got wedged up there?ü§î

On our Oregon road trip, I figured out the best way to warm up this winter is to soak in a hot spring in the forest. We must've spent hours relaxing in this spring, so I stayed refreshed by sipping on @drinkbai's Jamaica Blood Orange Bubbles. A couple years back, I cut out soda altogether by swapping it out for sparkling water, and this flavor has become one of my favorites! #BetterWithBai #BaiPartner

Let the rain fall. 
It was so funny...driving from California back to Seattle after the holidays, the whole trip was super sunny until I hit Oregon. Immediately as I crossed over the border, clouds and fog engulfed the entire sky. I know losing sunshine would probably bum a lot of people out, but I just smiled. Because even though I moved awhile ago now, it was the very first time that heading to the PNW truly felt like I was going home.

Happy New Year friends!! Welcome to 365 days full of endless possibilities. New Years has always been my favorite holiday because I love a good blank slate. I take a few hours on every Jan 1 to reflect on the past year of growth, then write out a ton of new goals (in all areas of life) that motivate me to start crushing another year. 
What goals are you guys working towards in 2020? Would love to hear!

Photo by @watchluke / my edit

One of the prettiest falls I‚Äôve ever set eyes upon. It‚Äôs name in Javanese loosely translates to a thousand waterfalls.

Photos of me by @mikesugianto / my edits
The famous Avatar Mountains. This place has probably the most unique landscape I‚Äôve seen anywhere in the world. Which view do you guys think is better, from above or down below?

One more fall appreciation post because I‚Äôm in denial it‚Äôs already the holidays and almost a new decade! But really, I‚Äôm planning some snowy winter destinations to shoot early 2020. Where do you guys think I should go?

First photo by @earthtoraymond / my edits

The next post in my top photos of 2019 countdown!

Photo 3: Autumn‚Äôs Arrival

My second year chasing fall colors in New England, I knew I needed to go back and capture more of these trees lit up in brilliant reds, oranges and golds. Finding proper color is actually harder than it sounds...you need near perfect timing, which really means being willing to drive hours at a moments notice to anywhere peak color might be starting.
‚Ä¢
Me and @earthtoraymond spent two weeks camping, hiking and shooting, but this shot was actually the very first we took on the trip. I flew into New York straight from a gig in the Caribbean, then we drove 7 hours to northern New Hampshire where I thought fall colors might be starting to turn, slept in the car a couple hours, and hiked up to this point for sunrise. When we got up there, it was completely socked in by fog and we thought it was a total bust. But 20 minutes later it opened up and we saw this brilliant view for the first time. After a first morning this crazy, I knew we were in for a good trip.
Because two camels are better than one. üê™üë©üèª‚Äçü¶∞üê™ Photo by @mikesugianto / my edit

‚ÄúYou can‚Äôt connect the dots looking forward. You can only connect them backwards. So you have to trust that the dots will connect somehow in your future.‚Äù You guys, my very first podcast interview on @polarpro‚Äôs Golden Hour is now live! Had a blast recording this one...this is the first time I‚Äôve had the chance to chat through all my past experiences in photography, modeling, and PR and how all those gigs got me to where I am today (plus I make a big biz announcement üòâ). The links in my bio if you wanna check it out! If you get a chance to listen, message me and let me know what you think üíï

Last December, I was flying high in a heli over Fjordland on the South Island of New Zealand, gliding over glaciers, alpine lakes, and mountain peaks. One of the most memorable experiences of my life (especially because ironically I‚Äôm terrified of flying, ha!), I‚Äôm 100% convinced that this is the most beautiful place on the planet.

First and last photo shot by @ryanresatka / my edits
Santa‚Äôs reindeer and I hope you have a Merry Christmas! üéÑü¶åüéÅ‚ú®

Don‚Äôt mind me, just camping in the Jordanian desert, waking up for sunrise, and being as extra in photos as humanly possible. Casual Wednesday right?

Photos by @mikesugianto / my edits

The last image in my 2019 countdown...my favorite photo of the year!

Photo 1: Falling Fire

I‚Äôve done a Yosemite winter trip every year for the past five years, and this image is almost that long in the making. It was on one of those first trips, sitting in the lodge, that I heard about this natural phenomenon called firefall. For just two weeks in February, the sunset lines up perfectly with Horsetail Falls, lighting it up so that it literally looks like a waterfall made of fire. 
However, in order for this to happen, conditions have to be absolutely perfect. This means no clouds, which is pretty rare in February, and the right amount of melting snowpack for the waterfall to be flowing. Aka if you want to see this thing you gotta get really lucky. 
I first saw it in 2017, when we practically stumbled onto it happening. I didn‚Äôt have the proper camera gear to shoot it well, but I was completely in awe watching it happen, the craziest optical illusion I‚Äôve ever seen. 2018 comes around and I‚Äôm determined to shoot it this time, but there‚Äôs a drought which means no snow and therefore no waterfall.

This year, I knew it had to be my year. I went to the park for five days and figured if I tried every single night, eventually I‚Äôd get good conditions for it. On our third night, all the elements lined up perfectly. Fresh snowfall from the day prior was getting blown off the cliff by gusts of wind, illuminating like flames dancing through the air. Everyone watching it happen was saying it was the best firefall conditions in a decade. 
I‚Äôm standing there with my tripod surrounded by other photographers, freaking out it‚Äôs so beautiful, when out of the corner of my eye I saw a bird was about to fly into frame. Hit the shutter a few times hoping for the best and managed to capture it in the shot too. Between stubborn determination and a whole lot of luck, this shot become one of the highlights of my entire photography career so far.

I‚Äôve said it before and I‚Äôll say it again: the redwoods will forever be my favorite place in the world. In a place so still and ancient, with trees that are thousands of years old, it blows me away how it somehow seems entirely different each time I visit. When I drove this back road through the forest a year ago, it was so foggy it was almost eerie. But this time around we stumbled onto these brilliant warm light rays, giving it an entirely different feeling.

A waterfall oasis tucked away in the middle of the desert. We backpacked 10 miles in 102 degree heat with full sun exposure on 2 hours of sleep to get here. So when the trail finally opened up to this view, I honestly thought I might be hallucinating.

Chasing waterfalls in central Oregon. There are so many gorgeous falls in the PNW, that we were able to see three in one day on this trip!

I get asked at least a few times a week where my yellow jacket is from, and @eddiebauer's Charly Jacket has become my go to. Perfect for providing that bright pop of color in adventure photos, plus it kept me completely dry in torrential downpours and walking under waterfalls. #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor

On our last day in Saudi Arabia, me and @thewayfaress went on a wild 4x4 adventure, ripping through the desert for hours until we finally arrived at this mind blowing cliff edge. Honestly no photo can really do justice to the sheer scale of this place. Named the Edge of the World, it most definitely lives up to its reputation. @saudi_airlines #saudia #welcometoarabia #ad

Sending it into 2020 like... You guys the Live Your Dreams workshop launches TOMORROW Monday 1/6 at 8am PT. I‚Äôve been working on this online course for over a year now, so I‚Äôm beyond excited to get it into your hands!

The workshop is a business course that walks you through, step by step, exactly what I did to become a full time travel photographer and influencer. We‚Äôll start at the very beginning, building your brand - including how to build a following on Instagram - move into how to pitch brands and land high paying gigs, then conclude with everything you need to know to run your own business as a full time creative freelancer.

So many of you guys have asked me how I do what I do, so I‚Äôm super stoked to offer this course that shows you exactly that. Plus you‚Äôll be added to a private, students only Facebook group where I‚Äôll be providing direct mentorship to all my students.

Check out the link in my bio to learn more! I‚Äôll be running a discount offer for launch day only, so keep an eye out.

In these photos snapped in the middle of the desert, I‚Äôm wearing an abaya, the traditional dress that Saudi women wear. One of my goals is to get more immersed in the local culture when I travel, so going shopping for my very own abaya was a highlight of my recent trip with @saudi_airlines. The shop attendant was so excited we were taking an interest in their traditional clothing, it was a really gratifying moment of human connection. #Saudia #WelcomeToArabia #Ad

Becoming one with the desert. I always seem to gravitate towards orange and gold environments these days...I‚Äôve realized they tend to put me in my most creative mind set. Everyone‚Äôs getting excited for winter right now, but all I can think about is returning to a place like this. @saudi_airlines #saudia #welcometoarabia #ad

My photo schedule while on the road is a wild one: wake up for sunrise, shoot, answer emails, drive to another location, shoot sunset, edit photos, sleep a few hours, repeat. That may sound like a grind, but honestly, I wouldn't have it any other way. I'm able to experience and capture so many incredible moments in nature this way, like stumbling onto this back road through the redwoods, lit up with golden light. 
For these sometimes sleep-deprived trips, I rely on @javamonster for that extra surge of energy to keep me going and always chasing the adventure. #JavaMonsterPartner #Sponsored

I‚Äôve been craving a new creative challenge recently, so I started messing around with editing short video clips in Premiere. I have absolutely no clue what I‚Äôm doing, but it‚Äôs gratifying to start completely fresh at something and figure it out one step at a time. Stoked to push it further in 2020.

Song: Floor Seats, A$AP Ferg

Video clips shot by @mikesugianto

I didn‚Äôt have the proper camera gear to shoot it well, but I was completely in awe watching it happen, the craziest optical illusion I‚Äôve ever seen. 2018 comes around and I‚Äôm determined to shoot it this time, but there‚Äôs a drought which means no snow and therefore no waterfall.

This year, I knew it had to be my year. I went to the park for five days and figured if I tried every single night, eventually I‚Äôd get good conditions for it. On our third night, all the elements lined up perfectly. Fresh snowfall from the day prior was getting blown off the cliff by gusts of wind, illuminating like flames dancing through the air. Everyone watching it happen was saying it was the best firefall conditions in a decade. 
I‚Äôm standing there with my tripod surrounded by other photographers, freaking out it‚Äôs so beautiful, when out of the corner of my eye I saw a bird was about to fly into frame. Hit the shutter a few times hoping for the best and managed to capture it in the shot too. Between stubborn determination and a whole lot of luck, this shot become one of the highlights of my entire photography career so far.

Happy New Year friends!! Welcome to 365 days full of endless possibilities. New Years has always been my favorite holiday because I love a good blank slate. I take a few hours on every Jan 1 to reflect on the past year of growth, then write out a ton of new goals (in all areas of life) that motivate me to start crushing another year. 
What goals are you guys working towards in 2020? Would love to hear!

Photo by @watchluke / my edit

Can you believe this natural Turkish hot spring is over 2,000 years old? Now a UNESCO World Heritage site,  it‚Äôs Turkish name directly translates to Cotton Castle. We had a fun morning running around, exploring every single pool. On our road trip around the country, we discovered Turkey is full of ancient gems like this one.

Photos by @mikesugianto / my edits

Let the rain fall. 
It was so funny...driving from California back to Seattle after the holidays, the whole trip was super sunny until I hit Oregon. Immediately as I crossed over the border, clouds and fog engulfed the entire sky. I know losing sunshine would probably bum a lot of people out, but I just smiled. Because even though I moved awhile ago now, it was the very first time that heading to the PNW truly felt like I was going home.

I‚Äôve been a total hermit at home the past couple days, staying up til 3am working on getting the Live Your Dreams Workshop ready to launch Monday morning (if you don‚Äôt know what I‚Äôm talking about, check out the ‚ÄúWorkshop‚Äù story highlight on my profile!). Confession: I have not put on real pants in over 48 hours and have been surviving solely off of hummus and la croix LOL glamorous, I know. 
So here‚Äôs a throwback to this gorgeous hike in Zion with the best 360 views. Very much looking forward to getting some fresh air and stretching my legs on a hike soon.

Photos of me by @mikesugianto / my edits

perPostData.comment: I love to be best, especially when it comes to sports. I often work my ass of to develop as an athlete, to be better and reach my goals. It's a great characteristics but everything good comes with something challenging. I'm bad at slowing down, do things without purpose or a goal. A constant aim for something greater, which often results in that I forget to enjoy what I have. To be satisfied and happy for what I've accomplished. I've worked a lot with this the past years, to stop, breath, look, do thing for pure fun and cherish myself. So this is a reminder to you guys out there, look at where you are, enjoy the ride and once in a while, stop for appreciation.

Back in the place of frozen lips and cold toes, the price you have to pay for hours surrended by snowy sceneryüóª

Photo: @emrikjanssonphotography

I've spent countless hours at sea. During the summers with my family we often took our boat to a remote island, to go for long swims and watch the seals sunbathing. Dad used to bring me out in the waves when windsurfing or rescue me when I was too tired. The ocean is such an essential aspect of my life and could never see myself spending too much time away from it.  A few weeks back, I got the opportunity to join @sjofartsverket for a day at sea to experience how they work. We took the pilot boat to look at the ships, I learned about the education they do and how they jump (!!) from the boat to the ship to make the route to land as safely as possible. Ships were massive I tell you. Cool to get out from my own life bubble and see something entirely different for a day. Have a look in my stories to see more. #samarbete #sverigesvackrastearbetsplats

First backflip post of the year! Here is to many more üçª
Photo by Mr @adamklingeteg

Mentally warming myself up by thinking about this day. My cold and fever is finally gooone and I've been able to spend a cold day outside skiing. It's also the first day in the past days that my mind haven't been racing, been stressed out without any real reason lately. I can feel a clear connection to my mental well being and moving my body, do any of you feel the same?

Leaving home to join the jury at @ispo.acceleratingsports in Munich for a few days judning snow hardware 2020. I'm looking forward to see all the new innovations within snow sports and meet everyone, honored to be part of the crew. See you again soon mountains!
‚úñÔ∏è‚úñÔ∏è‚úñÔ∏è‚úñÔ∏è‚úñÔ∏è
Captured a crisp morning by @adamklingeteg

Breathing in the fresh air, walk up mountains, go to the beach or stay in bed.
This piece of technology facilitates my lifestyle and I could never do what I do today without it. Taking my office with me wherever I go, capture moments for Instagram or interacting with companies through google apps. Its been a great journey to try something else and realize that everything is way easier with my Samsung Galaxy s10plus (which I highly doubted in the beginning). #TeamGalaxy #WithGalaxy''

Home dressed in the golden December light. Feels good to get those legs going, spend hours outside and hang around with friends.

You don't need much but you need the right equipment, especially during winter. So I bought new tent equipment from @naturkompaniet this year. To facilitate for more of those moments. perPostData.comment: Insert motivational phrase about never looking back or opening a window or closing a door or some üí©.... Nah, no need for that, you‚Äôre all rockstars.... Last day on the Canary Islands was good ol fashion fun. From a photo standpoint the light was absolute garbage, so I just putzed around looking at plants, talking to random goats, and workin on my trail twerkin (more like finger gun dancing, pew pew). Hiked up and down a few thousand feet, drank a cold beer, watched the sunset, and currently devouring the first hamburger I‚Äôve had since I‚Äôve left home! It was perfect. Off to France tomorrow for the @salomonfreeski MTN Collective! Rock n freakin roll ü§òüèº‚Äî‚Äî-> @salomon #timetoplay #salomonwmn

Fun Fact: If you don‚Äôt rehash your year on Instagram - you incinerate. So cheers to 2019! It was a goodie. Japan, Flat Out Friday moto race, solo pack rafting the Escalante River, riding through mainland and Baja, Mexico, Montenegro for @salomon #salomonwmn week, taking the FXR through Europe, backpacking through the Winds with my closest friends and boyfriend, paddleboarding all of Lake Powell with my best friend, and finishing with another #mtncollective with @salomonfreeski in France! Infinitely grateful for this life and the people in it. Thank you to my sponsors for supporting me year after year, couldn‚Äôt do this without you. Love you all, thanks for following, and hope you have a killer 2020! #happynewyear

#MTNCollective 2019! First three days were in the classroom, brushing up on first aid and rescue and then today we had the privilege of going to @telepheriquelagrave for skiing! Beautiful as always and felt great to get some turns in. Now we finish up the week at @val_thorens to freeride, test gear, and make some pretty photos! Life is good!! @salomonfreeski #timetoplay #salomonwmn üì∏ @drewpeterski

It was windy as f#!%*, so here‚Äôs a selfie! After my first attempt of setting up my tripod only for it to be instantly knocked over, I thought I outsmarted the elements by strapping my backpack to it and adding rocks. Only problem is - I‚Äôm on a volcano surrounded by nothing but pumice, which weighs NOTHING! So yeah, had to pack the tripod away, so just a good old fashion cheesin at the camera had to do. Hiking around Pico Viejo was surreal. I was in a completely different world. It was cold, windy, with snow capped peaks surrounded by red moonscape and sparse canary pine. I honestly forgot I was on a tropical island. It‚Äôs fascinating being in a place that‚Äôs filled with lush warm beaches and water, yet holds Spain‚Äôs tallest mountain. Sigh, I might not leave ü•∞ üòú @salomon #timetoplay #salomonwmn

Cheesin for many reasons... throwback to Europe on the FXR this summer. It‚Äôs funny being back over here, in the same town in the UK where I finished my trip, this time putzing around in a little rental Fiat. Doesn‚Äôt quite have the same feel as the @sscycle 111‚Äô motor with @legendsuspensions Revo Piggy Backs üòÇ but it‚Äôs fun to come full circle and reflect back on a wonderful summer filled with adventure and travel üòä @revit_urban #revviturban

Heyo! #MTNCollective day something or other. When fun is had - you lose track. Today we skied. It felt damn good. Round 3 tomorrow! @salomonfreeski #timetoplay üì∏ @evans_leah @mikedski and @lovisa.rosengren ‚ù§Ô∏è

What an incredible week in France with @salomonfreeski. Bringing the crew together to not only continue our backcountry education and expanding the range of gear, but to cultivate the bonds we have between each other. It‚Äôs one thing to have a sponsored freeski team, it‚Äôs another to have a freeski family - and that‚Äôs exactly what we are. We support each other to the ends of the earth and back. We hoot and holler and hug it out. We high five, talk shit, and lift each other up. The banter is brutal, the support is solid, and the love is endless. This is difference and something I‚Äôm so proud to be a part of. Love you nerds! Let‚Äôs blow this season out of the water! #mtncollective #salomonwmn üì∏ @arthurbertrand_photos

Utah is off to a hell of start! Had to bop overseas but stoked to get home to more of this!! (Actually knowing my luck high pressure will follow me, but let‚Äôs hope not). Safe riding everyone, especially if you‚Äôre heading into the backcountry!! üì∏ @iancrossett @salomonfreeski #timetoplay #salomonwmn

Thank you @brundagemtn for another wonderful holiday week! Every year I look forward to skiing my home mountain, and every year there‚Äôs powder to ski. But besides great skiing, you always bring the best vibe and the most fun! Smiles for miles every direction I look. Can‚Äôt wait to come back for more üôèüèº ‚Äî‚Äî> üì∏ @iancrossett @salomonfreeski #timetoplay

Gear Talk Time. Between tried and true gear that sees every adventure with me, to new toys like paddleboards, paddles, and coolers, I learned a lot from our Lake Powell thru-paddle last month. Overall I was REALLY satisfied with what we brought. The cooler was handy not only for fresh produce, but as a seat for when we were feeling tired. The solar panel combined with the battery pack easily lasted through the trip. We were warm and toasty every night, and never felt too beat down thanks to the swift hard boards and the super light paddles. Only thing I would change would be a longer board. I‚Äôm excited to use the 12‚Äô6‚Äù for shorter trips, but the 14‚Äô model would have been better due to the longevity of the trip. Otherwise everything we brought was spot on (well, maybe a little too much white wine, but better safe than sorry).
-------> Want to learn more about what I brought? Check out my story to see what gear was essential and swipe up to learn more. If you see something you like, punch in the code KALEN to receive 15% off at checkout on your first order with @backcountry (some restrictions apply). Happy gear hunting my friends! #findyourbackcountry #sponsored
Moody Wasatch. Hopefully this wind calms down so we can get back to fluffing ourselves üíÅüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è ‚Äî‚Äî> @salomonfreeski #timetoplay

Did you really go skiing if you didn‚Äôt get a tip shot?? Honestly it‚Äôs more fun skiing than taking photos anyway, so tip shots are an easy way to show off the goods without sacrificing ski time ü§™. Luckily the @lifeproof N√ãXT keeps my butterfingers from ruining my new iPhone 11, so I can take as many photos of the front of my skis as I want, regardless of the elements or m slippery hands. ‚Äî‚Äî> Check my story to learn more about their cases, from dirt proof to integrated wallets, then swipe up to get 20% off using code KALEN20 #showusyourproof #ad

perPostData.comment:
After months on the road, I‚Äôm so happy to be back in Joshua Tree! üòÉ I had such a great season here last winter, and am stoked to start thrashing my skin on some new, hard projects! Haha. Here‚Äôs a little throwback to a fun send last year on an unnamed V6 in the Real Hidden Valley. I was pretty psyched to find some cool short-people beta on this climb by using a knee bar! Swipe over to watch a little send clip!  I‚Äôve always been hesitant to post videos due to beta spraying, but people really seemed to enjoy my last video on Yogi Variation, so I thought I‚Äôd start posting more of them.  I‚Äôd love to hear your thoughts about it!  Beta videos...Yes? No? .

It‚Äôs amazing how quickly the time and miles pass by!  Today, we‚Äôre driving through a rainy PNW, only a couple days from home!  Hard to believe it was almost three months ago that we first passed through this area, heading North to Alaska! it still feels like yesterday. What a crazy trip it‚Äôs been!  Here‚Äôs a little throwback to that first PNW visit, having a little fun hanging out on Leavenworth classic, Sleeping Lady! üòÉ.
. üì∑ @bobbysorich

Happy New Year: Part 2 - On How I Spent 2019 üßó‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüßó‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüßó‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.

Kind of like a crack climb, 2019 was a year of distinct parts, with some hard moves and grrr faces along the way! The first half of the year was spent working incredibly hard, balancing full time finance, part time route setting, and freelance creative jobs with climbing and training!  It was all in an effort to accomplish a long held dream of road tripping to Alaska!
.

I pushed too hard though, ignored several warning signs, and ended up taking a fall that severely injured my back. But our bodies are amazing things, and with lots of rehab and training, by early summer I was healthy and climbing again! Just in time for the second half of the year...The Great Alaskan Road Trip!!! üòÉ
.

@bobbysorich and I had the car packed and were set to leave in a few days time, when another driver failed to yield at an intersection and smashed into my passenger side! üò¶ I remember sitting there all dazed and confused, not really understanding what had just happened. Then someone shouted for an ambulance and I came to my senses. Thankfully, everybody involved ended up being okay, but my car was totaled. At first I was devastated. This couldn‚Äôt be happening. Not right now. Not after my back. Not after working so hard! Maybe it was rash and irresponsible, but I stubbornly refused to let the accident ruin my dreams of Alaska. I raced out to buy a new car, and within a week @bobbysorich and I were on the road! .

Over the next five months, we experienced incredible adventures, sent our hardest climbs, shot some amazing creative projects, and spent quality time with family and friends! We also learned a lot about ourselves, relationships, and the realities of living in tiny spaces. .

Overall, it wasn‚Äôt the easiest year, but it was an incredible year! I had so many wonderful opportunities, and learned a lot about balance, resilience, and believing in oneself!  I‚Äôm really proud of all the hard work that went into making this year happen, and so grateful to everyone that supported me along the way! I‚Äôm really excited for all the adventures and lessons yet to come in 2020!! . üì∑ @bobbysorich

Happy New Year: Part 1 - On How I Rang in 2020! üò¥üò¥üò¥
.

Besides spending one day at home on the boat, where all I did was repack my bags for Joshua Tree, December 29th marked five months of being on the road, five months of big adventures and living in the tiny space of a Subaru! Though @bobbysorich and I had been hoping to stay in Joshua Tree through the new year, instead, we began to realize just how exhausted and burnt we were from our road trip. For several nights in JTree I couldn‚Äôt sleep at all, any little hiccup in the day would send me spiraling into tears, and I was climbing terribly! üòï And so, we did the unexpected thing, packed up, and went home early. New Year‚Äôs Eve and New Years Day were spent sleeping, eating, visiting friends, watching movies, riding bikes, and putting together a puzzle. For once, we didn‚Äôt climb or take photos or think about work responsibilities, and honestly it was AWESOME!! I tend to push too hard, always feeling pressure to work towards the next goal, and this New Year was a much needed reminder that life requires balance! We all need to make space for our physical and mental well being!  After just a few days at home I‚Äôm already feeling so much better, and can‚Äôt wait to take on 2020!  Wishing you all a year of good health and great adventures!! ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è
.
.

Anyone who knows me, knows I‚Äôm not exactly a cold weather climber. üòè The majority of my big sends have been in the 90 degree blazing sunlight, and I tend to start shivering when the temps dip below 75. Sending tons of gratitude out to this guy today!! Bobby and I met Cody (@climby.meadows) earlier on our trip in Squamish. In between crushing v11s, he chatted with us about his upcoming move to Anchorage, Alaska, where he was going to be working as a setter at the Alaska Rock Gym. It felt like fate!  We told Cody we‚Äôd be up in Alaska soon too and he encouraged us to come compete at the annual Pumpkin Pump bouldering comp at the @alaskarockgym. We made it to Alaska just in time and had such a blast competing! .

Over the next month and a half, Cody constantly went out of his way to make us feel at home in Alaska, training with us at the gym, and showing us around town. Cody helped bring me on board as a guest setter, and made it his personal mission to make sure we got in some outdoor climbing, no matter how much snow we had to trek through!  He also put up with me forcing him to take this portrait because I liked the color of his jacket, so that says a lot! Haha. .

If anyone out there wants more info on climbing in Alaska, or plans to visit and needs some local beta, @climby.meadows is your guy!  Cody, I‚Äôm so stoked we ran into you in Squamish! Thanks for being such a kind and awesome person!! üôè üôèüôè .

Happy New Year: Part 1 - On How I Rang in 2020! üò¥üò¥üò¥
.

Besides spending one day at home on the boat, where all I did was repack my bags for Joshua Tree, December 29th marked five months of being on the road, five months of big adventures and living in the tiny space of a Subaru! Though @bobbysorich and I had been hoping to stay in Joshua Tree through the new year, instead, we began to realize just how exhausted and burnt we were from our road trip. For several nights in JTree I couldn‚Äôt sleep at all, any little hiccup in the day would send me spiraling into tears, and I was climbing terribly! üòï And so, we did the unexpected thing, packed up, and went home early. New Year‚Äôs Eve and New Years Day were spent sleeping, eating, visiting friends, watching movies, riding bikes, and putting together a puzzle. For once, we didn‚Äôt climb or take photos or think about work responsibilities, and honestly it was AWESOME!! I tend to push too hard, always feeling pressure to work towards the next goal, and this New Year was a much needed reminder that life requires balance! We all need to make space for our physical and mental well being!  After just a few days at home I‚Äôm already feeling so much better, and can‚Äôt wait to take on 2020!  Wishing you all a year of good health and great adventures!! ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è
.
.
.

Happy New Year: Part 2 - On How I Spent 2019 üßó‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüßó‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüßó‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.

Kind of like a crack climb, 2019 was a year of distinct parts, with some hard moves and grrr faces along the way! The first half of the year was spent working incredibly hard, balancing full time finance, part time route setting, and freelance creative jobs with climbing and training!  It was all in an effort to accomplish a long held dream of road tripping to Alaska!
.

I pushed too hard though, ignored several warning signs, and ended up taking a fall that severely injured my back. But our bodies are amazing things, and with lots of rehab and training, by early summer I was healthy and climbing again! Just in time for the second half of the year...The Great Alaskan Road Trip!!! üòÉ
.

@bobbysorich and I had the car packed and were set to leave in a few days time, when another driver failed to yield at an intersection and smashed into my passenger side! üò¶ I remember sitting there all dazed and confused, not really understanding what had just happened. Then someone shouted for an ambulance and I came to my senses. Thankfully, everybody involved ended up being okay, but my car was totaled. At first I was devastated. This couldn‚Äôt be happening. Not right now. Not after my back. Not after working so hard! Maybe it was rash and irresponsible, but I stubbornly refused to let the accident ruin my dreams of Alaska. I raced out to buy a new car, and within a week @bobbysorich and I were on the road! .

Over the next five months, we experienced incredible adventures, sent our hardest climbs, shot some amazing creative projects, and spent quality time with family and friends! We also learned a lot about ourselves, relationships, and the realities of living in tiny spaces. .

Overall, it wasn‚Äôt the easiest year, but it was an incredible year! I had so many wonderful opportunities, and learned a lot about balance, resilience, and believing in oneself!  I‚Äôm really proud of all the hard work that went into making this year happen, and so grateful to everyone that supported me along the way! I‚Äôm really excited for all the adventures and lessons yet to come in 2020!! . üì∑ @bobbysorich

What a crazy and wild ride 2019 has been! I feel like it‚Äôs gone by in a blink of an eye and now we‚Äôre on to the next decade! I‚Äôm excited for not only my adventures of 2020, but how I‚Äôll grow and evolve even more starting with settling down a bit and finally getting an apartment üòú . Happy New Year‚Äôs Eve everyone! ‚ô•

‚ô•
 4. Finding my love for hot springs in Oregon and soaking in them until my hands were complete prunes ü•µ ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚ô•

‚ô•

‚ô• 
7.  Spending an entire month in Turkey and falling in love with its vast and varied terrains üíï ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

‚ô•

10.  Freezing my ass off in Montana and loving every minute of it ü•∂

I‚Äôve had some time to think about what changes I want to make in the New Year and this year I want to focus on being REAL.
‚†Ä
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
Being real with myself and how I feel‚Äî‚Äî- I want to step away sometimes and be able to be introspective about what I need for my mental health. Like finding more stability and routine in 2020 and being okay with not always taking the most exciting route, but the one that‚Äôs best for my wellbeing at the time. ‚†Ä
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢ ‚†Ä
Being real with you guys‚Äî‚Äî-‚Äî things aren‚Äôt always peachy and perfect in my life. I think they rarely are all the time for everyone,  and that‚Äôs okay. I want to share more of myself on here with you guys, both the ups and downs. ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
Being more real with my friends and family‚Äî‚Äî-not always worrying about saying and doing the right thing to  make everyone happy.‚†Ä ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢

Hey it‚Äôs me ‚úåüèª ‚†Ä ‚†Ä

I get asked a lot about how I afford  to travel all the time and what I do for a living ‚Äî here‚Äôs my story: ‚†Ä ‚†Ä

I started this Instagram account when I was in university in 2016 as a fun way to share my travel photos when I was studying abroad. It was nothing more than a distraction from the senioritis I was feeling on the last leg of university. However, starting that account in the OG days of Instagram, I gained a small following on it! I got asked to do some brand deals in the early days, but right before I graduated I also snagged an online project management gig, where I was remotely managing a brand‚Äôs social media and blog. That was enough to convince me not to take on a ‚Äúreal job‚Äù right away and instead go on a trip to SE Asia. One thing led to another and I never really stopped traveling üôà. About a year ago, I quit my online job and fully jumped into working and as a content creator. My full time career right now is content creation. I work with and bring brands all over the world with me. I share them on this platform, as well as create content that they use for themselves. It‚Äôs an exciting concept to work for myself while simultaneously being able to share my creativity and passion for adventure on this platform. It‚Äôs an interesting career that I never thought I‚Äôd be in, but I‚Äôm addicted to the freedom it provides. I hope that gives some clarity haha üòå

Shot by @jguzmannn with my edits

This past month, I've been on the go more than not, usually getting up way too early to adventure around and explore beautiful spots. I usually don't have time to grab breakfast and by the time mid-morning hits, I get hangry. This time around, I brought a bunch of @powerupsnacks with me to much on the go. They're full of nutritious wholesome ingredients like nuts, berries and even dark chocolate! Bringing a bag along on any adventure, is a great way to curb your appetite while getting a bunch of protein, antioxidants and omegas from real ingredients you can see! *ad #powerupsnacks

Winter is officially here and I don't know about you guys, but my lips always take a beating in cold temperatures! There's nothing worse than dealing with dry, chapped lips on top of being cold all the time haha. I've partnered with @softlipslipbalm and using their Slim Sticks has been keeping my lips hydrated through the winter. My favorite flavor is vanilla, but they also come in a variety of fruity flavors like Watermelon and Raspberry and has SPF 20 for extra protection! Grab them at the check-out in Target, Walmart or Dollar General. #softlipsslimsticks *ad

perPostData.comment: A few years ago Nick bought me a welder for Christmas. At first I was really excited and then soon after I became overwhelmed and a little bit scared of the heavy machine. I‚Äôm embarrassed to admit that I was nervous to learn something new, constantly told myself I was too busy to learn and doubted that I could even do it. Even though the welder sat in a closet unopened for almost two years, I imagined one day learning how to weld and dreamt of all the things I would create. I still have dreams of creating furniture, art, and even railings for our home one day. This past year, @acehardware has been a constant and amazing supporter of mine. They have encouraged me to continuously be creative and have motivated me to step outside the box of everyday life and routine to create something new. With encouragement from my local Ace Hardware Store ( @salidaace ), I mustered up the courage to drag the welder out of the dark closet, dust off the box and open it for the first time. I then signed up for a couple of lessons and worked with @salidaace to get all of the necessary tools needed to begin welding on my own. I am still very much in the beginning phase and just learning and practicing the basics. I am grateful for this new creative outlet in my life and realize now that my hopes of creating the things I once imagined are actually in reach.¬†¬†#MyLocalAce #AcePartner @acehardware
Argentina ‚ù§Ô∏è

I love third wheeling with my sister. Last weekend I met up with Kenzie and her boyfriend and tagged along with them to go get a Christmas tree in the mountains behind their house (they are very cute). We skied in with friends and brought warm coffee & peanut butter chocolate hemp bars for some energy. It was the perfect day and began dumping snow as we skied our way back to the truck. This was a casual and perfect way to test out a new pair of skis I just got from backcountry.com. While I grew up skiing, I am very new to skinning up and the backcountry stuff but it is something I am eager to learn and get better at (it‚Äôs a killer workout!) I am moving to Steamboat Springs later this year and so excited to have some of Colorado‚Äôs best mountains out the backdoor. I‚Äôm hoping to take this learning curve easy and learn slowly, and most importantly put safety first always. Thank you to @backcountry for setting me up with my new skis, boots and bindings. They offer free 2-day shipping which is great this time of year with the holidays approaching quick and you can get 15% off your first order at Backcountry using my code MADDIEB15 (exclusions apply). Backcountry partners with the Nature Conservancy so please be sure to help give back to the outdoors by donating to @nature_org during checkout. #FindYourBackcountry #Sponsored #Backcountry
Brown trout and empanadas are on the horizon @revantoptics #RevantOptics #TeamRevant

I was fifteen when I picked up a fly rod for the first time. I was 23 when I began guiding professionally. I am 29 years old now and I love this sport and so much of the culture attached to it. Witnessing the use of chewing tobacco and dip is not foreign to me and I want to share this not to shame those that use it but rather as a reminder that the use of chewing tobacco is an unhealthy choice and does have negative perceptions. Chewing tobacco and dip is an addictive substance and in addition to jeopardizing one‚Äôs health, chewing, dipping and spitting can be very unappealing to a lot of people. Please remember that smokeless does not mean harmless. @therealcost #uncanned

Tuco is our first dog and he is 6.5 years old! Feels like just yesterday we brought the little brown ball of fur home. I honestly can‚Äôt imagine life without a dog now... the amount of love, happiness and laughter Tuco brings to us everyday has undoubtedly been one of the very best parts of my life ‚ù§Ô∏è#LiveMoreNow #BuffUSA @buff_usa
My baby niece and goddaughter ‚ù§Ô∏è Estelle Louise

*If you use CBD or are curious about CBD, this post is for you!

Has anyone else found the language around CBD dosage confusing? I did when I first started using CBD. I remember asking why it was not made more clear on the packaging? The reason for this is because the amount of CBD you should take depends on you and your own body. Generally, most CBD companies like @cbdistillery_ recommend 30-60mg per day for the average adult but again, this depends on what works best for you - it could be less or it could be more and it‚Äôs important to note that everyone‚Äôs body will react differently. When figuring out what dose is best for you, it‚Äôs recommended to keep track, test in small increases and don‚Äôt be afraid to increase your dose (taking an increased dose of CBD from @cbdistillery_ is not harmful). I grew up in northern Sweden, It's a cold and dark place during the winter months. We have a saying there that is more a rule than anything else: "There is no bad weather, only bad clothing". When you had to go outside on breaks in school you would be bummed and think that the teachers are evil and this is not true the weather is shit come on let us be insideeeeee (quote by 10 year old Malou). Now that i'm older I get it. I spend the winter months skiing in interior British Columbia, which isn't much warmer than where I grew up. It's cold, dark and it snows all the time. I've been testing out @thenorthfaceuk FUTURELIGHT products and being out in the elements when you have the right gear makes all the difference in the world.

#nkskserviceteam #NeverStopExploring #FUTURELIGHT

My favorite thing - Being outside. Growing up I got pretty lucky in being able to choose my chores.
Cleaning up horse poop was better than doing dishes. Moving rocks, building fences, digging holes. Anything to be outdoors. Not much has changed. While I might not be cleaning up after the horses anymore.. I take every moment I can to be adventuring. Nature has a way of healing, bringing me home. I feel this connection with others around me, my friends have the same inclinations. Texture, colors, the sounds and ever changing weather. If I were to say I am in love with something, it‚Äôs being outside with Mother Nature.

Sure, I did some fun stuff in 2019... but the biggest highlights of the year for me were financial ones.
.
‚Ä¢You see, I learned poor spending habits as a young adult. Credit cards were this magical thing and I had no idea of the consequences when used irresponsibly.
.
‚Ä¢I had low paying admin jobs for many years and not only could I never get a raise, but I was consistently living paycheck-to-paycheck and outside my means - thus continuing to use credit cards.
.
‚Ä¢And due to all of the above... I was unable to save. To build an emergency fund and to contribute anything substantial to my retirement plan.
.
BUT, as of today... the last day of the year I am completely debt free. I have a solid emergency fund/nest egg and I‚Äôve been investing heavily (over the last couple years) in my retirement plan in an attempt to catch up.
.
I felt a LOT of shame due to my financial situation for many years and it was something I kept hidden from the people in my life... but now, I feel so proud.
.
Truth be told guys, I couldn‚Äôt have done it without you and to say I feel blessed is the understatement of the year. It‚Äôs such an immense privilege to be able earn money through my photography and Instagram. A privilege I sometimes don‚Äôt feel worthy of. But here I am and I‚Äôm changed because of it. So, as always... thank you for being here and your support. I am eternally grateful. üôèüèº
.
Cheers to 2019, to fresh starts, positive changes and to an incredible year to come. Catch ya in the new year! ü•Ç

This overly-popular Washington hike used to be my least favorite. If you time it poorly it can feel like you are hiking in a parade - and I almost always timed it poorly. I just viewed it as exercise as opposed to any kind of therapeutic experience in nature. But then one day, almost three years ago, I left work early and headed out in the freezing temperatures for a sunset hike. Sunset was cold but beautiful and only a few short minutes after leaving the top I slipped on a patch of ice and broke my ankle.
.
It was an incredibly humbling experience for me - the helplessness, the pain, the surgeries and the recovery. But what‚Äôs funny is how much I‚Äôve come to love this trail ever since that happened. Granted, I do well to avoid the busiest days/times, but I see so much more beauty in the details now than I ever did before. @Athleta #Powerofshe #sponsored

Hola friends!! I‚Äôve got a Peru trip UPDATE to share! ü§ó If you signed up for trip email notifications, then you already know... ;)
.
When working with @Trovatrip on my Peru itinerary for this October, I originally made the choice to nix Machu Picchu. My options were to either do more of a hiking trip or more of a touristy trip, and I chose hiking - which did not include the iconic destination. But I realized after the fact is that people want to do BOTH!
.
Sooo‚Ä¶ exciting news, it‚Äôs now available as an optional add-on to the itinerary! ü•≥ This add-on would extend the trip by an additional day/night, but we thought it was a great thing to be able to offer people that won‚Äôt want to fuss with trying to arrange it for themselves.
.
Details about the trip can be found in the link in my bio! We made some updates to the website, so if you don‚Äôt see the info about Machu Picchu on the main page - try using your web browser instead. And for those who have already signed up and want to add Machu Picchu, simply email the kind folks over at @trovatrip and they will get you squared away. üôåüèº
.
It‚Äôs going to be an incredible trip! If you have any questions about the trip or even how traveling as a group with a bunch of strangers (soon to be friends) works - don‚Äôt hesitate to reach out!
.

in 2019 i left behind my ‚Äúdream‚Äù body and a whole lot of my toxic masculinity but there‚Äôs more to the story i‚Äôd like to share.
.
a year ago, i was in the gym daily, more muscular than ever and also more miserable than ever. my body wasn‚Äôt healthy, it was a prison, it was unsustainable and it was the most unhealthy i‚Äôve ever been.
.
something the gay community doesn‚Äôt talk about is how the pedestal of physical perfection creates a society that‚Äôs filled to the brim with the toxic masculinity we so desperately sought to escape in the first place. therefor, by playing into this myself, by seeing what guys were into, by watching what my instagram discover page told me was important in six pack after six pack photo, i became the very thing i saw was the problem.
.
listen, i‚Äôm in a better place now but i‚Äôll work through this for the rest of my life. while this post is proof of progress outwardly it will always be time to do the inward work of self love, of undoing toxicity in body image. day after day. for quite literally ever.
.
don‚Äôt get me wrong, i am not shaming people who go to the gym or who are muscular, it‚Äôs just that for me, those patterns were created in the most unhealthy mindset as a way to erase who i was and replace it with a body that would make everyone else happy but me.
.
i don‚Äôt share this to be encouraged or applauded. i share this because i know so many gay men who believe the only way they are worthy is if they make everyone else happy but themselves. it‚Äôs time to stop that.
.
i‚Äôm learning more and more that it‚Äôs the undoing, not the doing, that has been the least visible, the most lonely, and the hardest thing but it‚Äôs also been the most important. i‚Äôm excited for 2020 and to pursue a body that makes me happy. no one else.

i want to take a moment to talk about drag and about pattie and i want to do it as wyn, very much out of drag. muggle human time. me to you.
.
drag fascinates me. it‚Äôs a playground where anything is possible. it‚Äôs brought me closer to self love than i‚Äôve ever been before and simultaneously has confused the hell out of me.
.
i hopped into drag sight unseen. i‚Äôve spent the past year trying to understand who i am as a drag queen and is what i do even drag? am i even doing this right? these are questions that leave me thinking because i just like you, i‚Äôve only seen drag as pop culture would like me to see it. perfect make up, unreal performance ability, and a culture driven by ego. by what the queen can do alone, just her. what look she can clock, what she can do to outdo everyone else. do it all yourself, be the very best, or get off the stage.
.

in 2019 i left behind my ‚Äúdream‚Äù body and a whole lot of my toxic masculinity but there‚Äôs more to the story i‚Äôd like to share.
.
a year ago, i was in the gym daily, more muscular than ever and also more miserable than ever. my body wasn‚Äôt healthy, it was a prison, it was unsustainable and it was the most unhealthy i‚Äôve ever been.
.
something the gay community doesn‚Äôt talk about is how the pedestal of physical perfection creates a society that‚Äôs filled to the brim with the toxic masculinity we so desperately sought to escape in the first place. therefor, by playing into this myself, by seeing what guys were into, by watching what my instagram discover page told me was important in six pack after six pack photo, i became the very thing i saw was the problem.
.
listen, i‚Äôm in a better place now but i‚Äôll work through this for the rest of my life. while this post is proof of progress outwardly it will always be time to do the inward work of self love, of undoing toxicity in body image. day after day. for quite literally ever.
.
don‚Äôt get me wrong, i am not shaming people who go to the gym or who are muscular, it‚Äôs just that for me, those patterns were created in the most unhealthy mindset as a way to erase who i was and replace it with a body that would make everyone else happy but me.
.
i don‚Äôt share this to be encouraged or applauded. i share this because i know so many gay men who believe the only way they are worthy is if they make everyone else happy but themselves. it‚Äôs time to stop that.
.
i‚Äôm learning more and more that it‚Äôs the undoing, not the doing, that has been the least visible, the most lonely, and the hardest thing but it‚Äôs also been the most important. i‚Äôm excited for 2020 and to pursue a body that makes me happy. no one else.

2009-2019 üåà i think 2009 me would be real proud of 2019 me. pursuing drag has been like coming out all over again and i couldn‚Äôt have done it without you.
.
i am dedicated to making 2020 a year to spread love, acceptance and queerness in the outdoors and to fight for our one true queen, mother natch, even more.
.
