perPostData.comment:
I‚Äôm proud to say that almost every photo I‚Äôve posted in the past few months is from our property or in nearby mountains.
‚Üü 
I used to dream of traveling, of always being somewhere enviable- and that‚Äôs what I did for a while. But I rarely felt content- just restless. I was always trying to be somewhere else, to prove something, and definitely to escape from my feelings...
‚Üü 
And now that @charles_post and I are almost always home, after so many years of never being fully happy, I‚Äôve realized that you can be happy or unhappy anywhere. You have to take the time to do the deep work, and traveling can honestly make that process take a lot longer if you‚Äôre just checking off bucket list places instead of actually taking the time to BE somewhere (which can help us grow a lot).
‚Üü 
Because no matter how amazing life looks on the outside, it‚Äôs how you feel inside that counts.
‚Üü 
My happiness has increased so much since I decided to just be myself. Not some Instagram travel influencer, but an artist. An athlete. A Montana girl who kinda just wants to be in Montana. Really, just a person who wants to live the best life I can and help others do the same.
‚Üü 
So while I don‚Äôt know just where I‚Äôm going with my business, and I‚Äôm sure I‚Äôll want to travel more some day, I know I‚Äôm going to be home a lot more, grow inwards and stop distracting myself with what doesn‚Äôt really improve my life. I‚Äôm going to just enjoy my time with @charles_post and @mr.knute because they, more than anything else, help my happiness grow by the day.
‚Üü ‚Üü ‚Üü 
My final shop update before the holidays is tomorrow (Wednesday) at 3 p.m. MST. I‚Äôm so excited to share a ton of new goodies and get some out of stock favorites back in stock (in limited quantities!) Thank you for all the love this holiday season, it means more than I can say to our little family! // #rachelpohlart #mrknute #happytears #ahsaunas

Self care is not selfish, it‚Äôs not an indulgence. It is necessary for your physical and mental health.
‚öò 
You don‚Äôt need a bunch of money or leisure time to take care of yourself. And you should not wait until you ‚Äúdeserve‚Äù it or wait until you‚Äôve taken care of everyone else to think about your needs.
‚öò 
Self care CAN be getting a massage, a day at the spa, or hiring a personal trainer. It CAN be a juice cleanse or a facial or a superfood salad- but don‚Äôt be fooled into thinking that‚Äôs what self care is.
‚öò 
Self care is saying *no* and protecting your time. It‚Äôs drinking enough water every day and saying no to what makes you feel bad. It‚Äôs eating your favorite meal, taking moments to breathe mindfully, move your body, daydream a bit. It‚Äôs taking time to read a book, watch your favorite show, create, paint, play music.
‚öò 
Self care doesn‚Äôt have to be expensive and it doesn‚Äôt have to take more time than you can give to it. Anyone can slip in moments of calm, short periods of joy, and slices of self care when we can- but the first step is saying yes to those windows.
‚öò 
Everything you need to practice self care is right here. All you need is your brain to stop thinking self care is selfish and a few moments that are just for you, that you carve out whenever you have the chance, because you deserve to make more time for you. Ask for help so you can do more things you love. Tell people no who you don‚Äôt actually want to give your time to.
‚öò 
It‚Äôs not an indulgence after all to take care of yourself- it‚Äôs essential to your health and happiness!
‚öò ‚öò ‚öò 
I‚Äôm SO DELIGHTED to say my yoga mats are officially in stock! There‚Äôs a link to them in my bio or visit RACHELPOHLART.com. Mat and calendar orders will ship next week!!
‚öò 
And because I know this time of year can be hard in many ways, tag a friend who could really use some kindness.
In the comments say why they could use a yoga mat this holiday season, and the friend you nominate will be entered to win a free mat of their choice!! Winner is @mtn_babe_801 ! #rachelpohlart

These two are the best Christmas presents I could ever hope for.
‚Üü 
Remember that all the *things* you could ever give or receive are far less important than the people in your life. Your health, both mental and physical, the experiences you have and the way you make people feel are what counts.
‚Üü 
Happy holidays from our little family to yours!

It didn‚Äôt happen overnight. I didn‚Äôt just wake up one day with an art career, a husband, a dog, a house, and all of this.
‚ãí 
Ten years ago I graduated from high school with some big dreams of being an artist. Over the last decade I‚Äôve fought so hard for everything I have. At times I fought for my health, both mental and physical. At others I had to stand up to people and circumstances that threatened my dreams. I worked as a nanny and babysat for a long long time before I could support myself on my art. Since then, I traveled to a dozen counties and I‚Äôve already grown my business far beyond my wildest dreams... I married the man of my dreams and got a pup that loves the snow and cold as much as we do...
‚ãí 
But my greatest success in the last ten years is not what I‚Äôve acquired, accomplished, or where I‚Äôve traveled- but who I‚Äôve become. The peace I‚Äôve found in accepting who I am has allowed me to create a life I‚Äôm proud of and not one bound by other‚Äôs expectations.
‚ãí 
I‚Äôm really excited for the next ten years. I have a feeling I‚Äôm going to become even more ‚Äúme.‚Äù Set goals you guys- it works. People who don‚Äôt set goals don‚Äôt expect enough from themselves. Be disciplined, don‚Äôt worry if you change your dreams, but don‚Äôt be afraid to make things happen, make mistakes, make some magic.
‚ãí 
What are your intentions for this year and the next decade??
‚ãí ‚ãí ‚ãí 
Photo by @charles_post #adventuresamoyeds #hikingwithdogs #skiingwithdogs #mrknute #backcountryskiing #2020 #intentions #creativehappylife #artistslife

The days are now getting longer... though personally, I love the darkness.
‚ãí 
I love the cold, deep snow, and starry nights. I long for winter in the summer. I know I‚Äôm the opposite from many people, and it doesn‚Äôt make a ton of sense why I prefer short, bitter cold days to long, hot ones.
‚ãí 
Maybe it was how I was raised, maybe it‚Äôs because I‚Äôve been skiing for 25 years and it‚Äôs still my favorite thing to do.
‚ãí 
But maybe it‚Äôs because I tend to expect so much from myself, and the darkness gives me an excuse to rest more. In summer I become frustrated by the length of days, the heat, the general ‚Äúhurry up and get all the summer activities in‚Äù feeling. But winter says ‚Äúrest, recalibrate, create.‚Äù
‚ãí 
This is my season. The light, the alpenglow on snowy peaks, the color of quickening shadows, the contrast between beautiful sparkly days in the mountains and being tucked in beneath the stars at night, between cold that takes your breath away and a fire that warms your bones.
‚ãí 
Maybe I need to learn a thing or two from people who love summer- and maybe if you don‚Äôt love winter you can learn a thing or two from this perspective: without darkness, long summer days are so much less special. A year ago @charles_post and I bought our first home, nested on ten acres of land near these very mountains.

That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm proud to partner with @parksproject because our public lands need our help, now more than ever. Each @parksproject purchase directly contributes to one of 50+ non-profit groups protecting parks and public lands in North America, providing necessary funding for the ongoing care of National Parks and public lands. ‚ãí 
For example, with every Joshua Tree product sold (like this awesome tee I‚Äôm wearing!) together we support the monitoring and protection of trees in the park. I was lucky enough to climb and paint in Joshua Tree some years ago, and it‚Äôs a special place to me (anyone else been there?)
‚ãí 
It saddens me to know that Joshua trees are now struggling to survive. Invasive plants, fire, and climate change are taking an enormous toll. Volunteers and partners work hard to collect data, remove invasive plants, and create fuel breaks to protect a beautiful species that symbolizes California deserts. Like every Park these days, Joshua Tree is in a fragile state. Thankfully, due to the @parksproject partnership, 12,089 hectares of Joshua Tree have been restored!
‚ãí 
So if you‚Äôd like to give back to the places that give us so much, check out @parksproject !! Because here we are ALL land owners regardless of if we‚Äôve put down roots,¬†and together we can make a difference for our public lands. // #parksproject #protectwhatyoulove

Self care is not selfish, it‚Äôs not an indulgence. It is necessary for your physical and mental health.
‚öò 
You don‚Äôt need a bunch of money or leisure time to take care of yourself. And you should not wait until you ‚Äúdeserve‚Äù it or wait until you‚Äôve taken care of everyone else to think about your needs.
‚öò 
Self care CAN be getting a massage, a day at the spa, or hiring a personal trainer. It CAN be a juice cleanse or a facial or a superfood salad- but don‚Äôt be fooled into thinking that‚Äôs what self care is.
‚öò 
Self care is saying *no* and protecting your time. It‚Äôs drinking enough water every day and saying no to what makes you feel bad. It‚Äôs eating your favorite meal, taking moments to breathe mindfully, move your body, daydream a bit. It‚Äôs taking time to read a book, watch your favorite show, create, paint, play music.
‚öò 
Self care doesn‚Äôt have to be expensive and it doesn‚Äôt have to take more time than you can give to it. Anyone can slip in moments of calm, short periods of joy, and slices of self care when we can- but the first step is saying yes to those windows.
‚öò 
Everything you need to practice self care is right here. All you need is your brain to stop thinking self care is selfish and a few moments that are just for you, that you carve out whenever you have the chance, because you deserve to make more time for you. Ask for help so you can do more things you love. Tell people no who you don‚Äôt actually want to give your time to.
‚öò 
It‚Äôs not an indulgence after all to take care of yourself- it‚Äôs essential to your health and happiness!
‚öò ‚öò ‚öò

I‚Äôm proud to say that almost every photo I‚Äôve posted in the past few months is from our property or in nearby mountains.

I used to dream of traveling, of always being somewhere enviable- and that‚Äôs what I did for a while. But I rarely felt content- just restless. I was always trying to be somewhere else, to prove something, and definitely to escape from my feelings...
‚Üü 
And now that @charles_post and I are almost always home, after so many years of never being fully happy, I‚Äôve realized that you can be happy or unhappy anywhere. You have to take the time to do the deep work, and traveling can honestly make that process take a lot longer if you‚Äôre just checking off bucket list places instead of actually taking the time to BE somewhere (which can help us grow a lot).
‚Üü 
Because no matter how amazing life looks on the outside, it‚Äôs how you feel inside that counts.
‚Üü 
My happiness has increased so much since I decided to just be myself. Not some Instagram travel influencer, but an artist. An athlete. A Montana girl who kinda just wants to be in Montana. Really, just a person who wants to live the best life I can and help others do the same.
‚Üü 
So while I don‚Äôt know just where I‚Äôm going with my business, and I‚Äôm sure I‚Äôll want to travel more some day, I know I‚Äôm going to be home a lot more, grow inwards and stop distracting myself with what doesn‚Äôt really improve my life. I‚Äôm going to just enjoy my time with @charles_post and @mr.knute because they, more than anything else, help my happiness grow by the day.

Go easy on yourself.
‚Üü 
You‚Äôre going to make mistakes, fail, and face challenges- maybe you won‚Äôt be proud of how you handled them.
‚Üü 
But go easy on yourself.
‚Üü 
You will say hurtful words, and you won‚Äôt say anything at all when you should have. You won‚Äôt get everything done on your to do list. You‚Äôll be late, forget about important details, burn dinner, miss out on opportunities. You will eat a whole box of cookies.
‚Üü 
You will be tempted to criticize yourself for your failures (in a way you‚Äôd never criticize a friend).
‚Üü 
But go easy on yourself.
‚Üü 
Because when things are hard, you don‚Äôt need to beat yourself up, because making a mistake is hard enough without further compounding it with negative self talk. Instead, be kind and patient. Life happens, so move on with grace and remember that what you‚Äôre learning now can shape you into a better person tomorrow.
‚Üü

Not that long ago, we were all kids. And some day, we will be old (if we‚Äôre lucky). Time goes so fast- and it speeds up the older we get. So spend it how you want it, as much as you possibly can.

Want to know something funny?
‚ùÖ 
I didn‚Äôt share any of my art on here for a long while, then only occasionally. I was certainly pursuing a career as an artist, I just didn‚Äôt think this was a very important place to help that happen. It also made me feel vulnerable sharing my work with an audience I ‚Äúdidn‚Äôt know‚Äù- what if people didn‚Äôt like my art? What if they liked it but I knew I could do better??
‚ùÖ 
But if we wait until our work (whatever that may be) is perfect before sharing it with the world, we might never do so.
‚ùÖ 
My art business didn‚Äôt really flourish until I started really putting myself out there, began pouring my time and effort into my art AND sharing it. I realized the power of this platform then figured out how to grow my following- through just being myself and A LOT of effort.
‚ùÖ 
So my advice today is this: if there‚Äôs something you want to pursue, don‚Äôt wait for years like I did to share it with the world! Just start and don‚Äôt care so much about what *everyone* thinks. And if you put in the time on your craft and business, you too can make a career out of what you love. And no instagram is not the only way to make that happen! It has just been a really helpful tool for me to reach an audience :) ‚ùÖ ‚ùÖ ‚ùÖ

The days are now getting longer... though personally, I love the darkness.
‚ãí 
I love the cold, deep snow, and starry nights. I long for winter in the summer. I know I‚Äôm the opposite from many people, and it doesn‚Äôt make a ton of sense why I prefer short, bitter cold days to long, hot ones.
‚ãí 
Maybe it was how I was raised, maybe it‚Äôs because I‚Äôve been skiing for 25 years and it‚Äôs still my favorite thing to do.
‚ãí 
But maybe it‚Äôs because I tend to expect so much from myself, and the darkness gives me an excuse to rest more. In summer I become frustrated by the length of days, the heat, the general ‚Äúhurry up and get all the summer activities in‚Äù feeling. But winter says ‚Äúrest, recalibrate, create.‚Äù
‚ãí 
This is my season. The light, the alpenglow on snowy peaks, the color of quickening shadows, the contrast between beautiful sparkly days in the mountains and being tucked in beneath the stars at night, between cold that takes your breath away and a fire that warms your bones.
‚ãí 
Maybe I need to learn a thing or two from people who love summer- and maybe if you don‚Äôt love winter you can learn a thing or two from this perspective: without darkness, long summer days are so much less special. Without cold, the warmth of summer means less. Without the hard moments in our lives, we feel less gratitude for the truly great ones.
‚ãí 
So try to appreciate all the seasons, especially the season you‚Äôre in right now- even if it‚Äôs not your favorite. Everything is always changing- learn to see the beauty in that.
‚ãí 
Happy (belated) solstice to all of you!

But I‚Äôve changed a lot in this past year. I don‚Äôt care as much about what all but a handful of people think. I know that there‚Äôs beauty in the simple little things that maybe only I fully understand...

Because in the end it doesn‚Äôt really matter how everyone else felt about our lives- only we know if we‚Äôre living our best life possible, only we know what it feels like to be us.

Magic doesn‚Äôt have to be reserved for a few days a year... In fact, I think we can create our own magic, every day.
‚ùÖ 
What is ‚Äúmagic‚Äù?? It‚Äôs childlike wonder and curiosity. It‚Äôs believing that good things can happen... following your dreams and falling in love and going for a walk at sunset. It‚Äôs falling snow and allowing yourself to be present. Magic is looking up at the moon and the stars.
‚ùÖ 
What does *magic* mean to you?
‚ùÖ 
I made my ‚ÄúEh-Frame‚Äù painting into an even more magical scene! Should I bring more movement like this into my paintings??

The most powerful lesson I‚Äôve learned in the last decade is this:
‚Üü 
To live well you must learn to  L E T  G O.
‚Üü 
Let go of expectations, perfection, and of people and things that make you unhappy. Let go of trying to be everything to everyone, all the time.
‚Üü 
Let go of the past- good or bad. Of trying to always prove something. Let go of labeling yourself and others. Of blaming and shaming and judging. Of thinking you‚Äôre not good enough. Let go of thinking ‚Äúwhen ____ happens I‚Äôll be happy.‚Äù
‚Üü 
Let go of controlling everything. Let go of wishing you or the people around you were different. Let go of caring what strangers think, and of measuring your worth against them.
‚Üü 
Let go of good vs evil, black and white, right or wrong- and instead embrace other opinions and nuances.
‚Üü ‚Üü 
Let go of trying to *let go* perfectly. Because letting go is about release, not rejection. It‚Äôs about not holding on so tightly...
‚Üü 
Because once you start to let go, you‚Äôll find you‚Äôve been free all along. Because when you learn to move past which does not serve you (that you‚Äôre clutching onto so tightly) you can reach for what lights you up.
‚Üü ‚Üü ‚Üü 
This photo from a little nordic ski with @charles_post @mr.knute a few days ago sums up letting go of so much... and embracing the little happy moments that fill me up. Happy last day of the decade everyone!
‚Üü 
What are you letting go of this year?

It didn‚Äôt happen overnight. I didn‚Äôt just wake up one day with an art career, a husband, a dog, a house, and all of this.
‚ãí 
Ten years ago I graduated from high school with some big dreams of being an artist. Over the last decade I‚Äôve fought so hard for everything I have. At times I fought for my health, both mental and physical. At others I had to stand up to people and circumstances that threatened my dreams. I worked as a nanny and babysat for a long long time before I could support myself on my art. Since then, I traveled to a dozen counties and I‚Äôve already grown my business far beyond my wildest dreams... I married the man of my dreams and got a pup that loves the snow and cold as much as we do...
‚ãí 
But my greatest success in the last ten years is not what I‚Äôve acquired, accomplished, or where I‚Äôve traveled- but who I‚Äôve become. The peace I‚Äôve found in accepting who I am has allowed me to create a life I‚Äôm proud of and not one bound by other‚Äôs expectations.
‚ãí 
I‚Äôm really excited for the next ten years. I have a feeling I‚Äôm going to become even more ‚Äúme.‚Äù Set goals you guys- it works. People who don‚Äôt set goals don‚Äôt expect enough from themselves. Be disciplined, don‚Äôt worry if you change your dreams, but don‚Äôt be afraid to make things happen, make mistakes, make some magic.
‚ãí 
What are your intentions for this year and the next decade??
‚ãí ‚ãí ‚ãí

I‚Äôll be taking the next couple days off social media to recharge, reflect, and plan for 2020. There are so many positives to being able to connect and share online, but I do find my best thinking and creativity happens when I‚Äôm unplugged. I encourage you to do the same before we move into this next decade... you may just be surprised what your mind comes up with when it‚Äôs given a break from the constant bombardment of other people‚Äôs thoughts, opinions, and work üíõ Cabin: @TyeHaus, Washington

I took some time off social media between Christmas and New Years. The funny thing is, I regularly have forced social media breaks throughout the year - e.g. when I‚Äôm in the backcountry, on a long haul flight, or in a remote location. But that‚Äôs the difference, those instances are forced and not really my choice to make. I never mindlessly reach for my phone in those circumstances, yet in every day life I find myself unconsciously scrolling and using social media as a source of distraction üì± There‚Äôs nothing inherently wrong with that, but I just didn‚Äôt like that it had become such an ingrained habit. During my break I found that it wasn‚Äôt really until day 3 that I stopped mindlessly clicking on my favorite social media apps (usually IG or Twitter). I literally didn‚Äôt even realize I was doing it until the app would open up... isn‚Äôt that crazy?! It‚Äôs such an automatic behavior ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è I‚Äôm obviously back online now, but moving forward I do want to keep remembering to be as mindful as possible about what I‚Äôm consuming on social media. I‚Äôm not necessarily limiting my app usage, but I am catching myself when I start scrolling for no real reason other than for distraction or procrastination. Whats the longest you‚Äôve ever had a social media break for? Did it change the way you use the apps?

There‚Äôs so much power in stillness ‚ùÑÔ∏è In a world that is so busy it‚Äôs more important than ever to pause and appreciate the quiet moments. Breathe it all in, let gratitude flow through you, and then absorb that feeling into your memory forever ‚ú®

YOUR MOST ASKED QUESTIONS ‚ú® I love hearing from you guys, but I do get a lot of the same questions pop up in my DMs and comments... SO I have decided to do a little series of posts answering your most asked questions!
‚†Ä
üì∑ PART 1 üì∑ Q: How do you take selfies? / Who takes your photos?
‚†Ä
A: My husband, @MatthewHahnel, takes the majority of my portraits. We run our business together, he is open to me directing him on the kind of photo I want, and we have learned how to work well together over the years.
‚†Ä
In saying that, you don‚Äôt need an Instagram husband to take beautiful self portraits üòâ I have learned a thing or two over the years about taking solo selfies. Here are my top tipsüëáüèº
‚†Ä
{Save this post to refer to later}
‚ú®Invest in a tripod. Yes, they are kind of awkward to travel with but they make taking self portraits WAY easier.
‚ú®Use the self timer function of your camera (some also have built in intervalometers), or use a remote control shutter release.
‚ú®Before you run into frame, use a prop (like your backpack) to focus your camera on something where you will be standing. This will avoid any out-of-focus shots.
‚ú®You can also ask someone to take the photo for you! Make it as easy as possible by setting up the shot for them. Obviously use your judgment and be careful about who you pass your camera over to.
‚ú®Try not be to embarrassed. Yes, you probably look quite silly standing there posing in front of a tripod. But does it matter what those people around you think? You‚Äôll probably never see them again...
‚ú®Try using a prop if you‚Äôre a little awkward. This will give you something to do with your hands and could be as simple as using your jacket, hat, or bag.
‚ú®Go when the crowds are smallest. This usually means getting up early!
‚†Ä
That‚Äôs all IG will give me room to write! You‚Äôll find more tips on my blog (link in bio) üíõ
‚†Ä
Important: Don‚Äôt be an asshole when trying to take your selfies. Always be kind and respectful, share the location, and offer to help others get their shots (i.e. be a good human).

I took some time off social media between Christmas and New Years. The funny thing is, I regularly have forced social media breaks throughout the year - e.g. when I‚Äôm in the backcountry, on a long haul flight, or in a remote location. But that‚Äôs the difference, those instances are forced and not really my choice to make. I never mindlessly reach for my phone in those circumstances, yet in every day life I find myself unconsciously scrolling and using social media as a source of distraction üì± There‚Äôs nothing inherently wrong with that, but I just didn‚Äôt like that it had become such an ingrained habit. During my break I found that it wasn‚Äôt really until day 3 that I stopped mindlessly clicking on my favorite social media apps (usually IG or Twitter). I literally didn‚Äôt even realize I was doing it until the app would open up... isn‚Äôt that crazy?! It‚Äôs such an automatic behavior ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è I‚Äôm obviously back online now, but moving forward I do want to keep remembering to be as mindful as possible about what I‚Äôm consuming on social media. I‚Äôm not necessarily limiting my app usage, but I am catching myself when I start scrolling for no real reason other than for distraction or procrastination. Whats the longest you‚Äôve ever had a social media break for? Did it change the way you use the apps?

If you‚Äôre like me, you probably had no idea that tonight was SUPPOSED to be the Victoria‚Äôs Secret fashion show - but it was canceled.

I‚Äôve never watched this fashion event, because I never understood the point - and I‚Äôm not a masochist. I don‚Äôt buy bejeweled lingerie, wear feathered wings in the bedroom or have stems a mile long. I literally could not NOT relate to anything more.

But regardless of how I feel, the brand was finally called out for their unrealistic, unattainable and demoralizing beauty standards. So, they‚Äôve closed up shop on their big event. They‚Äôve yet to admit to the public that it‚Äôs because they know they need to redirect their marketing to more body inclusive... but baby steps.

So tonight, go love on some ladies who are the real super models of life. #normalizenormalbodies #victoriasecretfashionshow #everybodyisbeatiful #effyourbeautystandards #ihaveembraced

Photo by @kellylemon

Today my best little guy left us. Leo, you were so loved by the world and had so many friends, costumes, experiences and snacks! You were the king of @72andsunny_, you had your 15 seconds of fame on The Bachelor, you had the wickedest farts. You loved the beach, sleeping in my bed, going for car rides, your brother & sister, your aunties @jessdbrewer, @aahlixx and uncle @Rebeccaullman, and you hated the boys who broke my heart and getting your nails clipped.

You were so good to me and everyone‚Äôs lives you touched. I only hope I was as good to you. My heart is broken selfishly for the loss of you in my life, but relieved you will no longer be in pain. Thank you for bringing so much frenchie joy to the world during your short time here.

May you rest playfully on a dog beach with all of your friends and fans. Please no questions, only condolences and memories. üôèüèª

Dylan H Brown, it‚Äôs been a joy to experience life and especially these last three years with you. Adventures with you have included countless countries, thousands of miles by land, sky and sea, numerous nights under the stars, half a dozen hiking boots worn through and a lifetimes worth of pizza slices. You‚Äôre my best friend, my creative partner and now the papa to our puppy. Happy Birthday, thank you for letting me celebrate you - even though you hate the attention. ü•Çto another year in this crazy life together.

Personally, I‚Äôve never been one for New Years resolutions. Wrote one-deleted it.

They feel like fad diets you‚Äôre committed to for 30 days and then you‚Äôre just like, ‚Äúwhy am I drinking celery juice every morning? I hate celery juice.‚Äù BTW - if you‚Äôve already given up your celery juice cleanse, or had a glass of wine, or eaten bread, or skipped your workout like you SWORE you wouldn‚Äôt... no fret, you‚Äôve come to the right place.

Here‚Äôs something radical I‚Äôm going to try in 2020 that you might want to try, too...
not setting any resolutions (gasp!) and forgiving yourself for the ones you did make, but couldn‚Äôt keep... because unrealistic goals are tough.

Instead, try holding space for yourself. Take classes, make art, stretch your muscles and your mind. Spend a day on the couch or hike a mountain. Finish a project or start a new one. Eat a salad or eat a cheeseburger. Skinny dip in an alpine lake or wear cozies all day long.

Do whatever makes you, more YOU. There is no timeline for becoming you. And if it doesn‚Äôt happen in 2020, who cares. each day is a new day.

Photo by @dylan.h.brown

When people watch me tie my shoes (or do any other two-handed tasks, like, opening a water bottle, painting my fingernails, typing on a keyboard, zipping my coat or putting a bag into the over-head bin) the general sentiment is to tell me how amazing I am.

I‚Äôm not bothered by this, though I know many people with physical differences are.

Strangers telling you how amazing you are for performing every-day, mundane tasks can feel patronizing and humiliating, when all you‚Äôre trying to do is NOT stand out for once.

But here‚Äôs the thing... it IS amazing! It‚Äôs amazing that humans are built to adapt and are wired for resiliency.

It‚Äôs amazing that we get to own our stories and use them to start conversations, build human connection and demonstrate compassion.

It‚Äôs amazing to teach, to share, to normalize and to humanize the daily life a person with a physical difference.

I know many of you may not agree with me. And that‚Äôs OK. It takes time. But just know, the next time someone calls you ‚Äúinspiring‚Äù or tells you how ‚Äúamazing‚Äù you are... believe it! You have no idea what one person considers amazing or who‚Äôs life you might ACTUALLY inspire just by being YOU.

Thank you @lesleyannemurphy for encouraging me to share this video, and all the girls in the Bachelor mansion who wanted to learn how I painted my nails before rose ceremonies üòâüíÖüèº

To anyone who‚Äôs grieving - I see you.

I‚Äôve had moments of joy this week, but something about sharing my joy - or life - has felt ‚Äútoo soon.‚Äù I want to move forward, but I also don‚Äôt want the space I‚Äôm holding for Leo to get further away.

It‚Äôs as if social media expects we all just carry on, business as usual, after an uncomfortable loss. Instagram doesn‚Äôt offer a bereavement policy, because grief is uncomfortable ‚Äì especially when it‚Äôs other people‚Äôs grief in your feed. Yuck.

I know eventually the veil will be lifted, and I‚Äôll have to get back to some regularly scheduled sponsored posts and inspirational quotes ‚Äì I mean, cute outfits don‚Äôt make themselves! ‚Äì but in the meantime, I wanted to share my healing with you because that‚Äôs the only thing that feels honest right now.

If you lost a loved one over this Holiday season, you‚Äôre not alone. I feel how hard it is to open this app and pretend everything is normal.

So here‚Äôs an excerpt I love from @noraborealis that might comfort you or someone who‚Äôs experiencing grief. ‚ÄúGrief is kind of one of those things,¬†like, falling in love or having a baby or watching "The Wire" on HBO,¬†where you don't get it until you get it, until you do it.¬†And once you do it, once it's your love or your baby,¬†once it's your grief and your front row at the funeral,¬†you get it.¬†You understand what you're experiencing is not a moment in time,¬†it's not a bone that will reset,¬†but that you've been touched by something chronic.¬†Something incurable.¬†It's not fatal, but sometimes grief feels like it could be.¬†And if we can't prevent it in one another,¬†what can we do?

What can we do other than try to remind one another¬†that some things can't be fixed,¬†and not all wounds are meant to heal?¬†We need each other to remember ‚Äì to help each other remember,¬†that grief is this multitasking emotion.¬†That you can and will be sad, and happy; you'll be grieving, and able to love¬†in the same year or week, the same breath.¬†We need to remember that a grieving person is going to laugh again and smile again.¬†If they're lucky, they'll even find love again.¬†But yes, absolutely, they're going to move forward.¬†But that doesn't mean that they've moved on‚Äù

I‚Äôm hiking Mount Kilimanjaro!!! ‚Ä¶.and yes I‚Äôm afraid.

Since starting SheLift, I‚Äôve wanted to hike kili to show other that we can conquer any obstacle that stands in our way.

When I was invited to join a trek up the Marangu trail up Kilimanjaro THIS February, I wasn‚Äôt afraid of the 19,000‚Äô peak that stood in my path, or the mere 60 days I had to prepare.

But when the self-limiting beliefs that usually like to camp out in the back of my brain (waiting for their chance to make an appearance at vulnerable times like this) quickly started showing up to the party, I got scared.

I‚Äôm supposed to be this brave, one-armed-adventure-girl who can do anything but what if I CAN‚ÄôT do this? What if I don‚Äôt summit? What if I‚Äôm doing this because it seems like ‚Äúthe thing‚Äù the brave, one-armed-adventure-girl who can do anything is supposed to do? The first year Dylan and I were dating, he asked me to do something FAR outside of my comfort zone - he asked me to run away for Christmas and sail the islands of San Blas, Panama. I had never NOT celebrated Christmas, or been away from my family - let alone over seas with a new boyfriend - so this proposal had me riddled with uncomfortable firsts.

I had so much fear surrounding this trip it nearly broke Dylan and I up, as he saw I was beginning to crack under my tough girl facade. He was inviting me along to sail with him from Panama to Colombia over the course of 8 days and I had never even left the continent. I was told I could only pack what would fit in my backpack and one swim suit. (‚ÄúYeah right,‚Äù thought). So of course I started researching what this sail would entail and the first blog I came across was a top hit titled ‚Äúhow NOT to sail San Blas.‚Äù I read the woman‚Äôs account of being sardine packed on a 6 person sail boat with 12 other backpackers and fed nothing but crackers and rum for 7 days without seeing land. The woman endured bed bugs, sea sickness, sun stroke and stolen possessions. Panic kicked in.

Insecurity began to muster up every excuse it could for reasons why I shouldn‚Äôt go on this trip. I was convinced I was not cut out for this type of travel - I was a 5 star hotel kinda girl. To put my anxieties at ease, we worked together to book an experience that would be a compromise of adventure and comfort. We ended up getting lucky and found a lovely French couple that was chartering their boat through San Blas and has it listed on Airbnb. We had the boat all to ourselves and still had the rum ;) What followed were the most magical 7 days at sea, island hoping from one untouched sand bar to the next.

Though this trip terrified me in theory, it pushed me past my comfort zone and ended up becoming the start of my love for travel. It taught me it‚Äôs OK to choose yourself over the holidays and go on the adventure you want. It taught me it‚Äôs OK to wash your hair in the ocean, and let go of your expectations.

I hope you all get to round out your year and welcome the new with something that pushes you out of your comfort zone, too. ‚úåüèª

When people watch me tie my shoes (or do any other two-handed tasks, like, opening a water bottle, painting my fingernails, typing on a keyboard, zipping my coat or putting a bag into the over-head bin) the general sentiment is to tell me how amazing I am.

I‚Äôm not bothered by this, though I know many people with physical differences are.

Strangers telling you how amazing you are for performing every-day, mundane tasks can feel patronizing and humiliating, when all you‚Äôre trying to do is NOT stand out for once.

But here‚Äôs the thing... it IS amazing! It‚Äôs amazing that humans are built to adapt and are wired for resiliency.

It‚Äôs amazing that we get to own our stories and use them to start conversations, build human connection and demonstrate compassion.

It‚Äôs amazing to teach, to share, to normalize and to humanize the daily life a person with a physical difference.

I know many of you may not agree with me. And that‚Äôs OK. It takes time. But just know, the next time someone calls you ‚Äúinspiring‚Äù or tells you how ‚Äúamazing‚Äù you are... believe it! You have no idea what one person considers amazing or who‚Äôs life you might ACTUALLY inspire just by being YOU.

Dylan H Brown, it‚Äôs been a joy to experience life and especially these last three years with you. Adventures with you have included countless countries, thousands of miles by land, sky and sea, numerous nights under the stars, half a dozen hiking boots worn through and a lifetimes worth of pizza slices. You‚Äôre my best friend, my creative partner and now the papa to our puppy. Happy Birthday, thank you for letting me celebrate you - even though you hate the attention. ü•Çto another year in this crazy life together.

Today my best little guy left us. Leo, you were so loved by the world and had so many friends, costumes, experiences and snacks! You were the king of @72andsunny_, you had your 15 seconds of fame on The Bachelor, you had the wickedest farts. You loved the beach, sleeping in my bed, going for car rides, your brother & sister, your aunties @jessdbrewer, @aahlixx and uncle @Rebeccaullman, and you hated the boys who broke my heart and getting your nails clipped.

You were so good to me and everyone‚Äôs lives you touched. I only hope I was as good to you. My heart is broken selfishly for the loss of you in my life, but relieved you will no longer be in pain. Thank you for bringing so much frenchie joy to the world during your short time here.

May you rest playfully on a dog beach with all of your friends and fans. Please no questions, only condolences and memories. üôèüèª

To anyone who‚Äôs grieving - I see you.

I‚Äôve had moments of joy this week, but something about sharing my joy - or life - has felt ‚Äútoo soon.‚Äù I want to move forward, but I also don‚Äôt want the space I‚Äôm holding for Leo to get further away.

It‚Äôs as if social media expects we all just carry on, business as usual, after an uncomfortable loss. Instagram doesn‚Äôt offer a bereavement policy, because grief is uncomfortable ‚Äì especially when it‚Äôs other people‚Äôs grief in your feed. Yuck.

I know eventually the veil will be lifted, and I‚Äôll have to get back to some regularly scheduled sponsored posts and inspirational quotes ‚Äì I mean, cute outfits don‚Äôt make themselves! ‚Äì but in the meantime, I wanted to share my healing with you because that‚Äôs the only thing that feels honest right now.

If you lost a loved one over this Holiday season, you‚Äôre not alone. I feel how hard it is to open this app and pretend everything is normal.

So here‚Äôs an excerpt I love from @noraborealis that might comfort you or someone who‚Äôs experiencing grief. ‚ÄúGrief is kind of one of those things,¬†like, falling in love or having a baby or watching "The Wire" on HBO,¬†where you don't get it until you get it, until you do it.¬†And once you do it, once it's your love or your baby,¬†once it's your grief and your front row at the funeral,¬†you get it.¬†You understand what you're experiencing is not a moment in time,¬†it's not a bone that will reset,¬†but that you've been touched by something chronic.¬†Something incurable.¬†It's not fatal, but sometimes grief feels like it could be.¬†And if we can't prevent it in one another,¬†what can we do?

What can we do other than try to remind one another¬†that some things can't be fixed,¬†and not all wounds are meant to heal?¬†We need each other to remember ‚Äì to help each other remember,¬†that grief is this multitasking emotion.¬†That you can and will be sad, and happy; you'll be grieving, and able to love¬†in the same year or week, the same breath.¬†We need to remember that a grieving person is going to laugh again and smile again.¬†If they're lucky, they'll even find love again.¬†But yes, absolutely, they're going to move forward.¬†But that doesn't mean that they've moved on‚Äù

Personally, I‚Äôve never been one for New Years resolutions. Wrote one-deleted it.

They feel like fad diets you‚Äôre committed to for 30 days and then you‚Äôre just like, ‚Äúwhy am I drinking celery juice every morning? I hate celery juice.‚Äù BTW - if you‚Äôve already given up your celery juice cleanse, or had a glass of wine, or eaten bread, or skipped your workout like you SWORE you wouldn‚Äôt... no fret, you‚Äôve come to the right place.

Here‚Äôs something radical I‚Äôm going to try in 2020 that you might want to try, too...
not setting any resolutions (gasp!) and forgiving yourself for the ones you did make, but couldn‚Äôt keep... because unrealistic goals are tough.

Instead, try holding space for yourself. Take classes, make art, stretch your muscles and your mind. Spend a day on the couch or hike a mountain. Finish a project or start a new one. Eat a salad or eat a cheeseburger. Skinny dip in an alpine lake or wear cozies all day long.

Do whatever makes you, more YOU. There is no timeline for becoming you. And if it doesn‚Äôt happen in 2020, who cares. each day is a new day.

Instagram vs Reality - let‚Äôs have some real talk on vulnerability and mental health üíõ On my best days I feel grounded, confident, joy filled, strong, capable and totally in love with my life, the world around me and humanity at large. But I have come to understand that being human means experiencing the full spectrum of human emotions. Feeling sad, lonely, anxious, defeated, scared, angry... these feelings are not only valid but critical in order to process and evolve.

So on my quest to live a more authentic, honest life I‚Äôm challenging myself to be vulnerable to you all today in hopes that it may inspire you to be a little more vulnerable and honest to yourself and your community.

IT‚ÄôS OKAY TO FEEL ALL YOUR FEELINGS.

When you‚Äôre going through these moments of feeling challenging emotions the best things that you can do is to allow yourself the time and space to process and TRULY feel these feelings. My personal favorite ways to process my emotions are by talking openly and honestly to a friend, crying alone in my car as hard as I can and for as long as I need, journaling my feelings, seeing a therapist, meditating and spending time in nature.

You guys know I‚Äôm a huge proponent of rooting in positivity but I think it‚Äôs important to acknowledge that no one is happy and positive all the time. And if I‚Äôve learned anything over the years it‚Äôs the importance of making time and space to feel your feelings, even if it‚Äôs momentarily painful. Because our feelings need to be acknowledged and expressed in order to be released. When we swallow or ignore our feelings they will find a way to surface, whether that‚Äôs through illness, depression, emotional outbursts... The better we can become at acknowledging our feelings and expressing them in a healthy way that allows us to process and move on, the better our mental health will become.

So please just know, it‚Äôs okay to not be okay, it‚Äôs okay to cry, it‚Äôs okay to feel ALL the feelings. It‚Äôs all part of the beautiful journey of being human. I love you and I care about you and I hope my ugly cry face inspires you to have a good cry today or any day you need it üíï

Officially four weeks out of shoulder surgery!! I can‚Äôt even explain to you guys how amazing it feels to be able to walk outside and breathe fresh air! This was my third shoulder operation in three years and let me tell you it has not been an easy journey, but somehow I‚Äôve managed to stay (mostly) sane! Over the last month I‚Äôve repeated to myself over and over again - ‚ÄúI am strong. I am capable of overcoming great challenges. The universe gives me exactly what I need and what I can handle. I have so much to be grateful for. I will get through this.‚Äù I won‚Äôt pretend there weren‚Äôt dark and painful moments over the last few weeks but I am truly astounded by the power of positivity and gratitude. Rooting in a positive mindset has allowed me to bring humor to the most frustrating moments, to see the blessings in my challenges and to cherish the small victories like buttoning my pants, brushing my hair or short walks in nature, breathing fresh air.

Do you use a mantra or positive affirmation when you‚Äôre going through it? What about a gratitude practice? What are you thankful for in your life right now?

Thank you to @googlepixel for encouraging and sponsoring me to capture and share my positive mind set through this recovery process. 
#googlepixel #pixel4 #positivemindset #attitudeofgratitude #sponsored

Happy Birthday @haydenkortemoore - I love you to the moon and back. You are kind, generous, optimistic, soulful, talented and sweet! You deserve nothing but the best in this world. Thank you for being you and thank you for your loyalty and friendship. Here‚Äôs to many more years of adventures, giving back and lifting each other up ‚ù§Ô∏èüíô

2019 - 2018 - 2017 - what a blessing each one of these experiences has been.

In 2017 I had my first shoulder surgery after a dozen dislocations over 6 years. My mantra to myself at that time went something like ‚Äúafter I get through this everything is going to be better‚Äù

That shoulder never really healed properly and 11 months later I blew the other one out when I slipped running sprints barefoot in the grass. So in 2018 my mantra went something like ‚Äúno more bad things. Only good things from here on out‚Äù

And then in 2019 I got hit by a car skateboarding and blew it out again, I barely had a chance to realize what had just happened before the most powerful voice came in to my head and said ‚Äúyou are so lucky to be alive. You are strong. You are capable of overcoming great challenges and the universe gives you exactly what you need and only what you can handle‚Äù

As I look forward to 2020 there‚Äôs certainly a piece of me that wants to ask the universe for ‚Äúno more bad things‚Äù but that would really be a waste of a wish. Who‚Äôs to say these injuries were ‚Äúbad‚Äù? And who am I to try and control life? Instead I‚Äôll say that I am incredible blessed to have been tried, tested and to have had the opportunity for incredible growth during these times.

Because of these experiences I am more patient, more empathetic, more in tune with my body, more supported by my loved ones, more capable of vulnerability and more grateful for the simple joys in life.

So 2020, I surrender. Whatever it is that you bring forth I will do my best to fully embrace it. It‚Äôs all a part of the journey and I now know my strength. üôèüèº‚ô•Ô∏è

Over 12 million acres have burned so far - note that ‚Äúdeadliest and most destructive wildfire‚Äù in California history burned 2 million acres. 
The current land destruction is more than 5 times as much acreage as the recent Amazonian fires.

Maybe 2020 is the year that we all wake up and acknowledge that we are amidst a global climate crisis. Maybe this is the year that we vote for leaders that are going to prioritize the health of our planet and people over capital gains for the few.

Maybe we don‚Äôt just like and share this post but we each donate a few dollars or whatever we can to the organizations on the ground doing work to protect these vulnerable animals, land and people. 
Vic Fire Service - @cfavic 
Wildlife Rescue - @wireswildliferescue 
Red Cross - @redcrossau 
My heart goes out to all of those affected. ‚ô•Ô∏è

This morning my surgeon released me from my cage ‚ö°Ô∏èüñïüèº‚ö°Ô∏è ya girl‚Äôs freeeee!!!!!! ‚ô•Ô∏è I‚Äôve got a long road and a lot of hard work ahead of me over the next couple months. But I just want to say thank you to everyone that has been there for me during these challenging times. I am humbled and grateful beyond words for the love and care you‚Äôve given to me. I could not of done this without you. Thank you.

Through and through I am an athlete and nothing gives me more joy in this world than using my body - skiing, surfing and skating. I‚Äôm about to put my head down and give my üíØ to get back to it. ‚ô•Ô∏èüëäüèª‚ô•Ô∏è #thirdtimesacharm #roadtorecovery

Money is great. Power is cool. Things can be shiny. But have you ever experienced the pure euphoric bliss of choking on blower powder?

More and more my definition of success is about quality communion with nature. And that deep peace that ensues from connecting with the earth and knowing that, I too am nature, not separate but totally connected.

Thanks for capturing me in my element @meg_haywoodsullivan #35mm #happygirl
Ciao for now Winter ‚ùÑÔ∏è headed to warmer places to continue healing my little wing so I can get back to flying! ü§ôüèº‚ô•Ô∏è‚úåüèº #roadtorecovery

perPostData.comment:
Perspective.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
The sun went down after a long day of hiking on my first night in the Dolomites earlier this year and I found myself sitting in the closed dining room of my rifugio. Across he lobby, a group of mountain bikers filled the bar - cheersing beers, singing and dancing well into the early hours of the morning. But I sat alone, a table filled with maps of the Fanes-Sennes-Prags nature park graciously lent to me by the family that ran this particular alpine hut. I traced my fingers along lines on the maps to its highest peaks, jotting down distances and elevations and approximate times - working backward to figure out at what ungodly hour I would need to wake up to be where I wanted to be when the sun poked over the mountain tops. As I unfolded one of the creases I saw a familiar name ‚ÄúLago di Braies, Pragser Wildsee‚Äù I realized that we happened to only be a few kilometres from one of the internet‚Äôs favourite alpine lakes. A summit nearby was circled on one of the more well loved of maps and, without any cell phone service or wifi to verify, I made my way across the lobby into the bar, map in hand, navigating my way through a sea of Italian cyclists and inquired with the elderly man keeping bar. The bar was loud and our language barrier was apparent but I felt confident that he agreed with my hypothesis. And so, a little bit of research, a little bit of luck and a few too few hours of sleep later I was able to find a new perspective on an old favourite. #autumnInsouthtyrol #suedtirol #dolomites

We all know that what I realllly want under the tree this year is an infinite supply of bluebird backcountry days and nights spent under the stars‚Ä¶
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
‚Ä¶but when it comes to gifts that are (a little bit more) realistic I have partnered with @rei to share a list of gift ideas for your favourite adventure partner that are made to last. This could also very well be named a list of products that I recommend to every close friend that ventures out in the backcountry, a list of items I would invest in time and time again, a list of things I wish I had five years ago when I first started backpacking or maybe even a list of items that I would sell a non-vital organ to have with me in the wilderness. These are the things that I count on every single trip to keep me warm and safe and comfortable. And as a bonus, so many of the companies making these products that I love so dearly also happen to be pioneers in sustainability and caring for our planet. So if you‚Äôre (like me, last minute) looking for something that your wilder half will not only love but will last for far longer than it should but also is made by people who care about our planet‚Ä¶ have a look at my holiday gift guide story highlight!

‚ÄúWe have been to the moon, we have charted the depths of the ocean and the heart of the atom, but we have a fear of looking inward to ourselves because we sense that is where all the contradictions flow together.‚Äù ‚Äî Terence McKenna
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
These hidden contradictions that we all house within shape our world, from performance capabilities to our capacity to experience joy. Suffering is experienced when there is contradiction between how you define yourself (I am) and what the reality of life is mirroring back to you (how you are).
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
Life is happening on one big continuum. Learn how to meet yourself in the most simplest way and let all life‚Äôs contradictions, both within and without, knit together and show you what‚Äôs true. You might be surprised at what you find.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
I read these words from my friends @instillmeditation a few months ago, bookmarked them, screenshot them, set them to my screensaver for a period of time. And in this time of year most often associated with (at least a little bit of) chaos I think that the contradictions become more apparent, a gentle reminder that we are all working toward something.

I fell in love with this city almost a decade ago.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
It was my 21st birthday. My mom and I decided to go on a girls trip and after Paris and NYC and Vegas and the entire state of Hawaii were all veto‚Äôd we settled on San Francisco. I na√Øvely thought that, coming from Canada, February would be no different than July and we would be basking in California sunshine for a week. Ah, a time before the weather network was my home page. It rained, some of the coldest and more unrelenting rain I have ever experienced, for the entirety of our trip. We ran a cold, wet, muddy trail race, took a boat to Alcatraz, walked down Lombardo street, took photos at the Golden Gate bridge‚Ä¶. ate our bodyweight in sourdough - you know, the normal SF things. Looking back I don‚Äôt know how I loved that trip so much. Over the years I have come back more times than I am willing to count - an extended layover here and there, a marathon (maybe two), a weekend with old friend I hadn‚Äôt seen in too long‚Ä¶ any excuse I could find.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
There was a time in my life that I thought I wanted to live here. I could see myself running up and down these steep streets, becoming a regular in a coffee shop - I don‚Äôt think it ever really mattered what I did as long as I was here. Over the past month I‚Äôve spent more time in this city than in Calgary and in all honesty it is exactly what I imagined it would be. Coming here felt a little bit like home - @kelsealoha even came for a visit! But as my time here comes to a close I look back with almost a sense of nostalgia. San Francisco I love you - but its just about time for this little Canadian to head north.

The first time I visited this perch was just shy of three years ago. It was pouring rain and almost sunset and a group of friends and I huddled under an overhang of the nearby rifugio. The rain let up and we sprinted to the mountains with an almost child-like glee. Fast forward a year later and on a girls trip wherein we took too many coffee breaks on our way from visiting my family in the Austrian Alps and, once again, found ourselves sprinting out to the mountains as the light all too quickly disappeared. We took a few photos, made some silly jokes and retreated to the car where we sat in a parking lot under a sky filled with stars, ate cheese and planned for our week in the alps. On a last minute trip earlier this year with my mom and aunt I was able to sneak in a morning at this spot. I planned and calculated and compulsively checked the weather. I was so excited to share this place that I had grown to love with my family‚Ä¶ they clearly did not share my enthusiasm. The early morning wake up was met with resistance, some snoozing of alarms, a longer than necessary breakfast and some of the slowest driving I have maybe ever seen in my life. The sky lit up every shade of pink and purple as we were still an hour away. I could feel my eyes welling up with tears of frustration and my blood boiling. When we arrived at the parking lot I hastily packed my bag and ran out, a familiar run, to a rang of mountains I love so much. #autumnInsouthtyrol #suedtirol #dolomites
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
I included a little swipe of my three visits. 2017 with @itsbigben, @jesswandering and @michaelmatti. 2018 with @haydenkortemoore and @kelsealoha and 2019 wherein I had the mountain range to myself.

Depending on other people has never been something I am comfortable with. Earlier this year I wrote a list of things that I rarely do alone, things that I feel better more confident with a friend by my side. Travelling internationally, backcountry wilderness camping and taking photos topped that list. And so, in my mission to independence I decided to tackle the latter two in one foul swoop. I found a camera that I loved (@fujifilm_northamerica X-T30), locked myself in my house for a week watching YouTube tutorials, and then set out on my first solo backpacking trip with the mission to (firstly, not die) but also to take a few photos that I was proud of. I figured that if there was nobody around watching me play around with my camera, getting acquainted¬†with settings and running back and forth between my tripod and whatever perch I was sitting on... I would finally force myself to feel more confident capturing my travels the way I wanted to. And - it worked! Since that trip my camera and tripod hardly leave my side- including this recent trip the Italian Dolomites.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
Check out the link in my bio for all of the tips and tricks that I have learned (so far) to help you take the perfect adventure self portrait.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
Shot on @fujifilm_northamerica X-T30 + 50mm f/2.0 lens | ISO 80, f/2.0, 1/900 sec (#partner)

Is it too early to be counting down the days to gatorade coloured backcountry lakes?
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
This was the second of a set of back to back backpacking trips for me this summer. It had been about a week since I had last hopped in a shower or even attempted to run a comb through my hair. There were days of torrential downpour with afternoons spent hiding in my tent watching Netflix, mornings finding shelter to drink a cup of hot coffee and, when @ryanclennett joined me and the sun did finally poke through and put a halt to the rain it felt as though gale force winds took its place. On our final morning we expected nothing and prepared to pack up the tent in the same manner in which we set it up - holding on for dear life to anything that could possibly fly away and chasing after loose items that would inevitably break free. But as my sunrise alarm went off all that we heard was silence. No flapping of the tent, no rain‚Ä¶ I ran out, barefoot, to a glassy lake and a (nearly) cloudless sky. We made coffee, ate breakfast and packed up camp slower than we are used to - finding any excuse to stay just a little bit longer.

We hiked 12.5km, gaining over 1,300 meters of elevation with our heavy packs on to get to this point, the funny thing is that most of the people we shared this sunset dinner view with had driven the (vast) majority of that trek. They came with  everything needed to tightrope walk a kilometer(+) above the canyon floor and tulle filled wedding gowns and bottles of champagne and more than enough food to feed the Canadian military (I didn‚Äôt want to exaggerate). It was unseasonably hot that week and I had packed for the dead of winter - my feet were sore and face was dirty and I knew I probably didn‚Äôt have enough water for the 5(ish)km left of hiking before we reached running water and our campsite for the night. But this dinner was perfect. A few dozen people bursting at the seams with love - newlyweds, newly engaged couples, people celebrating a decade of marriage‚Ä¶ friends celebrating a love for a sport that scares the sh*t out of me. It was a pretty special space to share and a dehydrated dinner I won‚Äôt soon forget.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
I know that this caption ‚Äòshould have‚Äô probably been something about the New Year, the New Decade, resolutions and the holidays - time with friends and family - disconnecting to reconnect. But that has never been my reality for this time of year. Historically I have been sick over the holidays more than I have been healthy and this year was no exception. My entrance into the new decade was more akin to a fumble on the edge of a cliff edge than the graceful debut into 2020 that I envisioned. And if this rings true to you - you‚Äôre not alone. Its okay to have a rough start, its okay to feel defeated and to be not quite okay right now. January 1 is an arbitrary date on the calendar and, as I say most years around this time, maybe one day in the middle of June or October or the last day of March you will take your big life plan, light it on fire and walk blindly down a new path - nobody can tell you that it has to be today.

Perspective.
‚†Ä ‚†Ä ‚†Ä
The sun went down after a long day of hiking on my first night in the Dolomites earlier this year and I found myself sitting in the closed dining room of my rifugio. Across he lobby, a group of mountain bikers filled the bar - cheersing beers, singing and dancing well into the early hours of the morning. But I sat alone, a table filled with maps of the Fanes-Sennes-Prags nature park graciously lent to me by the family that ran this particular alpine hut. I traced my fingers along lines on the maps to its highest peaks, jotting down distances and elevations and approximate times - working backward to figure out at what ungodly hour I would need to wake up to be where I wanted to be when the sun poked over the mountain tops. As I unfolded one of the creases I saw a familiar name ‚ÄúLago di Braies, Pragser Wildsee‚Äù I realized that we happened to only be a few kilometres from one of the internet‚Äôs favourite alpine lakes. A summit nearby was circled on one of the more well loved of maps and, without any cell phone service or wifi to verify, I made my way across the lobby into the bar, map in hand, navigating my way through a sea of Italian cyclists and inquired with the elderly man keeping bar. The bar was loud and our language barrier was apparent but I felt confident that he agreed with my hypothesis. And so, a little bit of research, a little bit of luck and a few too few hours of sleep later I was able to find a new perspective on an old favourite. #autumnInsouthtyrol #suedtirol #dolomites

perPostData.comment:
While fires continue to ravage communities in Australia here are some current statistics to mull over:
6,300,000 hectares or 16,000,000 acres have been burnt. 24 people have been killed and another 6 missing. Half a billion animals have been killed. 2500 buildings have been destroyed with 1300 of those being homes. At least 200 fires are still burning all over Australia - many out of control. 
These statistics are obviously heartbreaking and it is easy to feel incredibly helpless, but it is also evident that the people on the front line are in need of as much help as possible. I know $5, $10, $20 feels like it wouldn‚Äôt do anything, but collectively it can rebuild lives, homes and communities. For organisations to donate to I have a list on my website (follow the link in my bio) and within my stories. I have also opened a print store on my website where 100% of the proceeds will go directly to the bushfire appeal. So please, if you are in the position to donate a few dollars, or have been wanting a print of mine, now is the time to act.
My heart goes out to all of those affected by these fires, everyone on the front line, all of the volunteers & aid workers, and hope rain reaches you soon!
P.S this is not a current bushfire image from Australia

Driving from Tasmania to Iceland in a custom self-built overlanding camper. I know I‚Äôve been a little deceptive about what this project and have dropped a few hints here and there, but as I‚Äôve just completed another lap around the sun today I think today is a good day to reveal what the full plan is ü§óüéâüöö
I‚Äôm currently half way through the build of this camper. There has been an incredible amount of research going into it, and after getting some insane quotes to have one built for me I knew the only way I could afford to do this was to build one myself. That‚Äôs the first part of this project, I definitely don‚Äôt have the skill set to be able to pull it off, but seeing each problem as an opportunity to grow and learn I am slowly getting this thing built!
The second part is driving from Tasmania to Iceland - how you ask?! I have to put the vehicle in a container twice, once from Darwin to Dili in Timor, and another from Indonesia to Malaysia. The rest of the way I‚Äôll be driving or taking ferries. Simple right?!
A videographer will be joining for for the entirety of the trip, so I‚Äôll be sharing photos every day, videos every week and if I can manage it a podcast series as well, all with the aim to bring you guys along for the ride with me so you feel like you‚Äôre riding shotgun too!
So that‚Äôs the rough outline, if you have any questions or words of support I‚Äôll get back to every single one of you over the weekend üòä
Video by @jonorosee

perPostData.comment: Magical does not even begin to describe springtime in New Zealand. I‚Äôve always traveled here in late summer to early fall missing out on what might now be my favorite time of year to visit. Nothing could have prepared me for how pretty the lupins are in peak bloom! Had so much fun frolicking around in this field with lupins as far as the eye could see.

Reposting one of my all time faves to start off the new year ‚ú® 
In other news, currently packing to jump on a plane later today and head someplace new!
A classic New Zealand view üá≥üáø

I‚Äôve seen photos of this place for years, but for one reason or another I‚Äôd never quite made it here. Well I finally made it and the crazy blue water definitely lived up to the hype! This was also my Mom‚Äôs instagram modeling debut, how did she do?! üòÖ
I haven‚Äôt had a chance to edit any photos from New Zealand yet but in the meantime here‚Äôs an old fave from Canada!
The most festive photo I could find! I hope everyone has an amazing Christmas and Happy Holidays!üéÑ Who can spot the troll? üòÖ

I still can‚Äôt believe this was real life! A highlight of 2019 for sure!

It definitely felt like I‚Äôd stepped into some kind of Dr Seuss world üçÑ

Although I‚Äôve definitely grown to love winter more over the past few years, I still find myself occasionally falling back into a love/hate kind of relationship with the cold. After returning from New Zealand just a couple of days ago I‚Äôve found myself wanting to hibernate for a bit. I‚Äôm sure that‚Äôs partially due to jet lag but it‚Äôs also hard to adjust back to Alberta temps after some beautiful summer days down under. But again I just needed to remind myself that winter really is what you make of it. Embrace it and get out in it and find activities you love and you will quickly find yourself enjoying those colder days. With only a few more days until it‚Äôs officially winter here in the Rockies I thought it was timely to remind myself to embrace my first winter up North! And it definitely doesn‚Äôt hurt that I have a package from @eddiebauer on the way with some new ski gear and other cozy winter stuff that I can‚Äôt wait to share with you guys! #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor

@eddiebauer also has 50% off on their website & in stores right now! Link in my bio ‚ú® Pictured ~ the Women‚Äôs Downlight Down hooded jacket in Viola!

It‚Äôs my first winter in the Canadian Rockies and I‚Äôm already even more blown away by this place. Officially we‚Äôre only just over one week in, but in reality it‚Äôs been wintery here for awhile now. To live in a place surrounded by such majestic mountain views definitely makes staying indoors not an option! @eddiebauer #LiveYourAdventure #EBContributor 
Who has plans to visit this magical place this winter?! üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

I‚Äôve only been back in Canada a few days and I‚Äôm already missing New Zealand like crazy! We had an absolute blast traveling around the South Island in our @madcampersnz van! The vans are so cozy and have everything you need including a fridge, sink and cooking facilities which definitely helps keeps costs down while on the road! They‚Äôre also fully self-contained which means you can stay in camping areas with little to no facilities! 
Has anyone else ever planned their next trip back somewhere before they even left?! üòÖ #madcampersnz -

Disclaimer - Always do your research on local camping laws and leave it better than you found it ‚ú®

From a moody evening aboard an insanely magical overnight cruise through Milford Sound with @realjourneys. Picture mountains rising up steeply from the fiords below with cascading waterfalls in almost every direction. To top it all off we even saw a pod of bottle nosed dolphins and the cutest little penguin! #MyRJMoment

Just a few of the many highlights of 2019! It‚Äôs been a wild year full of some big challenges, and a lot of change. I left the U.S after making my home there for the best part of 9 years and made the move North to Canada. Leaving Montana wasn‚Äôt easy by a long stretch but the promise of new adventures, along with my inability to ever stay in one place, meant it was time for a new challenge. Only a few months after moving I broke my ankle while on a backcountry trip in Colorado, a bit of a set back for someone who lives for adventure. I was unable to fully work for weeks and forced to cancel several trips I had been really excited for. I also met a bunch of new people this year, many of whom I now consider friends, and went on some of my favorite trips yet! Anyway thanks so much to everyone who‚Äôs been a part of my journey this year, it means the world to me! And here‚Äôs to another incredible year in 2020! Happy New Year! ‚ú®

The truth is, I've traveled around the world looking for peace, only to find it wasn't there. 
It wasn't until I stopped running and sat still, that I realized it was with me the whole time.
The miracle of surrender. .
PC: @kimmie.tu üíö @k.deer

The art of sitting still.
.
.
Meditation.

Daily life and stress and worries tend to get overwhelming at times. Seems like my brain never wants to shut off. I need creative outlets to focus on. I think that's why I love climbing so much. When I'm climbing it takes 100% concentration on the present moment. There is no time for your mind to wander. But it is extremely stressful sometimes.

Normally, mental and physical stress cause increased levels of the stress hormone¬†cortisol. This produces many of the harmful effects of stress, such as the release of inflammation-promoting chemicals called cytokines. Which can wreak havoc on your adrenals, effect your thyroid, which can create all sorts of problems like depression, lack of sleep, attention span, memory, mental health and the general ability to cope with shit.

Frequently, when I'm out climbing and I get stressed out, I'll take time for myself, walk away and sit quietly and just breathe. By simply sitting up tall and focusing on the breath,
maybe even forcing a smile,
you can control your mood, anxiety and stress levels.

Mindfulness meditation is simple... Find a place to sit comfortably, somewhere quiet and free of distractions. Breathe in and out focusing on the breath. When thoughts pop up, and they definitely will, acknowledge them and let them go. When your mind wanders just bring it back to the breath.
That's it.

Start small with 10 min a day, then work your way up to 30, and then an hour. The benifits of doing this are huge and you will notice a shift immediately. Don't worry about if you are doing it correctly.
Just sit still and breathe...
.

No energy gets created in the universe, and none is destroyed.
It simply gets reorganized. 
Every human, and every ecosystem in the universe has an energy. And we exchange those energies with each other.
In death, the collection of atoms of which you are composed,
a universe within the universe,
are repurposed.¬†Those atoms and that energy, which originated during the Big Bang, will always be around. Therefore, your ‚Äúlight,‚Äù that is, the essence of your energy will continue to echo throughout space until the end of time.
In this way, we are all connected. . . . .
Not a bit of you is gone, old friend. You are one with everything now.
Rest in peace Snickers.
.

Well another injury...Recovering pretty well from the left shoulder pain I decided to start a 7a- 5.11d as my next project. A pretty aggressive left 2 finger pocket to a powerful right hand throw, popping off tweaked my ring finger in a way that shot pain down my forearm. Still climbed the rest of the route to the crux and immediately felt it start to swell.
I spent the rest of the day resting and icing it. Today it feels only sore in the muscle so thankfully I think it will be ok in a few days. I'm taking a few days rest and then hopefully I'll be back to project.
Thankfully there is plenty of activities around camp to keep your mind and body occupied. I have been doing hours of meditation and spending time in this beautiful nature that surrounds me. I even cut my own hair today! 
Slacklining is something I have always wanted to learn, so now I get to. My left arm is pretty bruised and sore but with one more week here I'm positive I'll be able to hop back on the in no time.
.
.
.

On the day before I left I decided to give this climb a go. The previous week I went way too hard and was feeling quite a bit of pain in my left shoulder and forearm so I had been taking it sort of easy on pushing grades and climbing fairly mellow. I wanted to spend my last day giving it all I had left. This one was highly recommended so I went for it.
First go I took a nasty whipper sending me crashing into the tufa with my right forearm. Too up in my head and lots of noise, screaming babies and chaos down below I decided to come back in the evening.
We came back and I worked it a few more times only being able to get past the crux once, but still not feeling super confident about the beta. My skin and body was screaming enough. As the sun went down I decided to come back in the morning to retrieve my draws and try again.
With the help of a few amazing friends, @kimmie.tu, Will, Stephan and Tristen, we got out there at 6am and I got to work. Falling multiple times again in the crux I was almost ready to give up. My fingers were raw and blistered, body and shoulder aching I was ready to except this wasn't going to go for me right now. Kimmie wouldn't allow it.
You got this girl.
She worked through the beta with me and unlocked a new sequence. I knew I probably only had enough power and skin left to try one last time so I gave it everything I had. I sent it right as the sun was hitting the rock at 9:30am. It was the best feeling ending this trip on such a high. I cleaned my draws and ran back to camp just in time to catch my taxi out of Thakhek. Feeling so grateful. Thanks for not letting me give up Kimmie!
.
.
"Mon General" 6c 5.11a/b

Hey you wanna go climbing?
No, I'm hurt I'm taking a break.
Just climb easy stuff.

Whaaaat you're not climbing?!?!

I've been hanging out here in the jungle for 16 days now. I'm coming to the end of my journey and traveling on. It was a nice break from the world. I haven't been able to use my phone or have service out here, only the occasional hotspot from friends and a couple trips to town on rest days. But even then it was brief. I gotta say I didn't realize how connected I was. Having a world of information in the palm of your hand, access to anything at anytime, being able to scroll mindlessly out of boredom or see what your friends are up to. It was a little strange at first and weirdly found myself getting into my head a lot. Having crazy dreams and restlessness, almost like anxiety and loneliness.
I got injured and wasn't able to climb, so I was forced to rest and I had lots of time to myself. I started to use the time to meditate. To sit in my bungalow in the jungle for hours and listen to the wind and my breath. It was not easy and it took me a few days to really get used to it, but when I did it was magical. I started doing breathing exercises and focusing my energy on my body and healing.
Before I would wake up and reach for my phone and start to rush through my day. Out here I wake up with the sunrise, or before, and start to meditate and greet the day with new eyes and be completely present. It's such a simple thing to be fully present yet to most of us it's the hardest thing in the world.
I allowed myself to be fully present here. To feel all the feelings and connect with the amazing people around me. I worked through the pain in my body and was able to climb most days. Even though I didn't get to crush as many climbs as I wanted to on this trip I definitely grew in so many other ways. I pushed myself harder physically and mentally than ever and I am truly grateful for this experience. I'm grateful for the incredible people I met here and the moments I'll remember forever.
.
.
Thanks for the photo @jojoyees and everything. I hope to see you again soon. Xo

We came back and I worked it a few more times only being able to get past the crux once, but still not feeling super confident about the beta. My skin and body was screaming enough. As the sun went down I decided to come back in the morning to retrieve my draws and try again.
With the help of a few amazing friends, @kimmie.tu, Will, Stephan and Tristen, we got out there at 6am and I got to work. Falling multiple times again in the crux I was almost ready to give up. My fingers were raw and blistered, body and shoulder aching I was ready to except this wasn't going to go for me right now. Kimmie wouldn't allow it.
You got this girl.
She worked through the beta with me and unlocked a new sequence. I knew I probably only had enough power and skin left to try one last time so I gave it everything I had. I sent it right as the sun was hitting the rock at 9:30am. It was the best feeling ending this trip on such a high. I cleaned my draws and ran back to camp just in time to catch my taxi out of Thakhek. Feeling so grateful. Thanks for not letting me give up Kimmie!
.
.

The art of sitting still.
.
.
Meditation.

Daily life and stress and worries tend to get overwhelming at times. Seems like my brain never wants to shut off. I need creative outlets to focus on. I think that's why I love climbing so much. When I'm climbing it takes 100% concentration on the present moment. There is no time for your mind to wander. But it is extremely stressful sometimes.

Normally, mental and physical stress cause increased levels of the stress hormone¬†cortisol. This produces many of the harmful effects of stress, such as the release of inflammation-promoting chemicals called cytokines. Which can wreak havoc on your adrenals, effect your thyroid, which can create all sorts of problems like depression, lack of sleep, attention span, memory, mental health and the general ability to cope with shit.

Frequently, when I'm out climbing and I get stressed out, I'll take time for myself, walk away and sit quietly and just breathe. By simply sitting up tall and focusing on the breath,
maybe even forcing a smile,
you can control your mood, anxiety and stress levels.

Mindfulness meditation is simple... Find a place to sit comfortably, somewhere quiet and free of distractions. Breathe in and out focusing on the breath. When thoughts pop up, and they definitely will, acknowledge them and let them go. When your mind wanders just bring it back to the breath.
That's it.

Start small with 10 min a day, then work your way up to 30, and then an hour. The benifits of doing this are huge and you will notice a shift immediately. Don't worry about if you are doing it correctly.
Just sit still and breathe...
.
